# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tonne
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tonne/aircraft] An **aircraft** is a vehicle that can fly by gaining support from the air.
[src:tonne/aircraft] It counters the force of gravity by using either static lift or the dynamic lift of an airfoil, or, in a few cases, direct downward thrust from its engines.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Common examples of aircraft include airplanes, drones, rotorcraft (including helicopters), airships (including blimps), gliders, paramotors, and hot air balloons.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Part 1 (Definitions and Abbreviations) of Subchapter A of Chapter I of Title 14 of the U.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Code of Federal Regulations states that *aircraft* "means a device that is used or intended to be used for flight in the air".
[src:tonne/aircraft] The human activity that surrounds aircraft is called *aviation*.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The science of aviation includes the designing and building of aircraft, which is called *aeronautics*. a *crewed* aircraft is flown by an onboard pilot, whereas an unmanned aerial vehicle may be remotely controlled or *autonomous*, controlled by onboard computers.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aircraft may be classified by different criteria, such as lift type, propulsion (if any), usage and others.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The history of aviation spans over two millennia, from the earliest innovations like kites and attempts at tower jumping to supersonic and hypersonic flight in powered, heavier-than-air jet aircraft.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Kite flying in China, dating back several hundred years BC, is considered the earliest example of man-made flight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In the 15th century, Leonardo da Vinci created flying machine designs incorporating aeronautical concepts, but they were unworkable due to the limitations of contemporary knowledge.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In the late 18th century, the Montgolfier brothers invented the hot-air balloon which soon led to manned flights.
[src:tonne/aircraft] At almost the same time, the discovery of hydrogen gas led to the invention of the hydrogen balloon.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Various theories in mechanics by physicists during the same period, such as fluid dynamics and Newton's laws of motion, led to the development of modern aerodynamics; most notably by Sir George Cayley.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Balloons, both free-flying and tethered, began to be used for military purposes from the end of the 18th century, with France establishing balloon companies during the French Revolution.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In the 19th century, especially the second half, experiments with gliders provided the basis for learning the dynamics of winged aircraft; most notably by Cayley, Otto Lilienthal, and Octave Chanute.
[src:tonne/aircraft] By the early 20th century, advances in engine technology and aerodynamics made controlled, powered, manned heavier-than-air flight possible for the first time.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In 1903, following their pioneering research and experiments with wing design and aircraft control, the Wright brothers successfully incorporated all of the required elements to create and fly the first airplane.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In 1906 Charles Frederick Page was granted the first U.S. patent for an aircraft.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The basic configuration with its characteristic cruciform tail was established by 1909, followed by rapid design and performance improvements aided by the development of more powerful engines.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The first vessels of the air were the rigid steerable balloons pioneered by Ferdinand von Zeppelin that became synonymous with airships and dominated long-distance flight until the 1930s, when large flying boats became popular for trans-oceanic routes.
[src:tonne/aircraft] After World War II, the flying boats were in turn replaced by airplanes operating from land, made far more capable first by improved propeller engines, then by jet engines, which revolutionized both civilian air travel and military aviation.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In the latter half of the 20th century, the development of digital electronics led to major advances in flight instrumentation and "fly-by-wire" systems.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The 21st century has seen the widespread use of pilotless drones for military, commercial, and recreational purposes.
[src:tonne/aircraft] With computerized controls, inherently unstable aircraft designs, such as flying wings, have also become practical.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft or *aerostats* use buoyancy to float in the air in much the same way that ships float on the water.
[src:tonne/aircraft] They are characterized by one or more large cells or canopies, filled with a lifting gas such as helium, hydrogen or hot air, which is less dense than the surrounding air.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Other gases lighter than air also theoretically work; however, such gases also need to be safe for human use (non-flammable, non-toxic).
[src:tonne/aircraft] Small hot-air balloons, called sky lanterns, were first invented in ancient China prior to the 3rd century BC and used primarily in cultural celebrations, although they also had military purposes.
[src:tonne/aircraft] They, along with kites, were two forms of unmanned aircraft that originated from China.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Kites were also used in the military, but unlike sky lanterns, their flight is caused by the differences in air pressure beneath and above the kite.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A balloon was originally any aerostat, while the term airship was used for large, powered aircraft designs—usually fixed-wing.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In 1919, Frederick Handley Page was reported as referring to "ships of the air," with smaller passenger types as "Air yachts." In the 1930s, large intercontinental flying boats were also sometimes referred to as "ships of the air" or "flying-ships".
[src:tonne/aircraft] Lighter-than-air aircraft don't typically require a pilot's license in the United States.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In most countries in Europe, standards for flying Lighter-than-air aircraft tend to be stricter compared to the United States.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Heavier-than-air aircraft or *aerodynes* are denser than air and thus must find some way to obtain enough lift that can overcome the aircraft's weight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] There are two ways to produce dynamic upthrust—aerodynamic lift by having air flowing past an aerofoil (such dynamic interaction of aerofoils with air is the origin of the term "aerodyne"), or powered lift in the form of reactional lift from downward engine thrust.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aerodynamic lift involving wings is the most common, and can be achieved via two methods.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Fixed-wing aircraft (airplanes and gliders) achieve airflow past the wings by having the entire aircraft moving forward through the air, while rotorcraft (helicopters and autogyros) do so by having mobile, elongated wings spinning rapidly around a mast in an assembly known as the rotor.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Gliders were one of the first forms of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:tonne/aircraft] They are a special type of aircraft that doesn't require an engine.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The first person to successfully build a human-carrying glider was George Cayley, who also was the first to discover the four major aerodynamic forces.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The first powered aircraft (Airplane) was invented by Wilbur and Orville Wright.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A *rotary-wing aircraft*, *rotorwing aircraft* or *rotorcraft* is a heavier-than-air aircraft with rotary wings that spin around a vertical mast to generate lift.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The assembly of several rotor blades mounted on a single mast is referred to as a rotor.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) defines a rotorcraft as "supported in flight by the reactions of the air on one or more rotors".
[src:tonne/aircraft] Rotorcraft generally include aircraft where one or more rotors provide lift throughout the entire flight, such as helicopters, gyroplanes, autogyros, and gyrodynes.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Compound rotorcraft augment the rotor with additional thrust engines, propellers, or static lifting surfaces.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Some types, such as helicopters, are capable of vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:tonne/aircraft] An aircraft that uses rotor lift for vertical flight but changes to solely fixed-wing lift in horizontal flight is not a rotorcraft but a convertiplane.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The largest aircraft by weight and largest regular fixed-wing aircraft ever built, as of 2016, was the Antonov An-225 *Mriya*.
[src:tonne/aircraft] That Soviet-built (Ukrainian SSR) six-engine transport of the 1980s was 84 m (276 ft) long, with an 88 m (289 ft) wingspan.
[src:tonne/aircraft] It holds the world payload record, after transporting 428,834 lb (194,516 kg) of goods, and has flown 100 t (220,000 lb) loads commercially.
[src:tonne/aircraft] With a maximum loaded weight of 550–700 t (1,210,000–1,540,000 lb), it was also the heaviest aircraft built to date.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The aircraft was destroyed during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The largest military airplanes are the Ukrainian Antonov An-124 *Ruslan* (world's second-largest airplane, also used as a civilian transport), and American Lockheed C-5 Galaxy transport, weighing, loaded, over 380 t (840,000 lb).
[src:tonne/aircraft] The fastest recorded powered aircraft flight and fastest recorded aircraft flight of an air-breathing powered aircraft was of the NASA X-43A *Pegasus*, a scramjet-powered, hypersonic, lifting body experimental research aircraft, at Mach 9.68 or 6,755 mph (10,870 km/h) on 16 November 2004.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Before the X-43A, the fastest recorded powered airplane flight, and still the record for the fastest manned powered airplane, was the North American X-15, rocket-powered airplane at Mach 6.7 or 7,274 km/h (4,520 mph) on 3 October 1967.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The fastest manned, air-breathing powered airplane is the Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird, a U.S. reconnaissance jet fixed-wing aircraft, having reached 3,530 km/h (2,193 mph) on 28 July 1976.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The main feature of unpowered aircraft is the inability to directly provide thrust through its engines.
[src:tonne/aircraft] This means that all unpowered aircraft rely on the environment for sustained flight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Gliders, for example, take advantage of their aerodynamic properties to enable them to travel long distances.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Techniques such as thermal circling, where gliders fly into warm air which allows them to rise, prolong flight time.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Due to the lack of an engine, initial propulsion assistance is usually necessary to ensure flight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A common glider launching method is aerotowing, where another aircraft tows the glider to an altitude from which sustained flight is possible.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Steering for a glider is also rudimentary, while more complex gliders like sailplanes usually have joysticks for steering, more basic aircraft like hang gliders rely on the pilot's physical coordination to change the centre of gravity.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A powered aircraft is an aircraft with a source of mechanical power, used to produce thrust.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Such sources are generally engines, as is the case with airplanes, but can be human-powered in more extreme cases.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Propeller aircraft, as their name suggests, rely on propellers to produce thrust for the airplane.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Compared to engines using propellers, jet engines can provide much higher thrust, higher speeds and, above about 40,000 ft (12,000 m), greater efficiency.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Although some rotorcraft, such as rotor kites, can be unpowered, most rotorcraft are powered by either piston engines or turboprops.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Some rotorcraft, including autogyros and gyrodynes, are propelled by a conventional propeller or jet engine, with the rotor unpowered, but most modern rotorcraft have a powered rotor, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Autogyros and gyrodynes are steered using a rudder, similarly to propeller and jet aircraft, and rotorcraft with powered rotors, such as helicopters, turn by adjusting the pitch of the rotor cyclically, so that the rotors on one side produce more lift than the other.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Rotorcraft with powered rotors typically need a tail rotor to counter the rotational torque produced by the rotor, which can cause the helicopter to spin.
[src:tonne/aircraft] An *aerostat* or *lighter-than-air aircraft* relies on buoyancy to maintain flight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aerostats include unpowered balloons (free-flying or tethered) and powered airships.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The relative density of an aerostat as a whole is lower than that of the surrounding atmospheric air (hence the name "lighter-than-air").
[src:tonne/aircraft] Its main component is one or more gas capsules made of lightweight skins, containing a lifting gas (hot air, or any gas with lower density than air, typically hydrogen or helium) that displaces a large volume of air to generate enough buoyancy to overcome its own weight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Payload (passengers and cargo) can then be carried on attached components such as a basket, a gondola, a cabin or various hardpoints.
[src:tonne/aircraft] With airships, which need to be able to fly against wind, the lifting gas capsules are often protected by a more rigid outer envelope or an airframe, with other gasbags such as ballonets to help modulate buoyancy.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aerostats are so named because they use aerostatic buoyant force that does not require any forward movement through the surrounding air mass, resulting in the inherent ability to levitate and perform vertical takeoff and landing.
[src:tonne/aircraft] This contrasts with the heavier-than-air aerodynes that primarily use aerodynamic lift, which must have consistent airflow over an aerofoil (wing) surface to stay airborne.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The term has also been used in a narrower sense, to refer to the statically tethered balloon in contrast to the free-flying airship.
[src:tonne/aircraft] This article uses the term in its broader sense.
[src:tonne/aircraft] An *aerodyne* is a heavier-than-air aircraft that relies on aerodynamic lift, or upthrust produced by the airflow, to fly.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aerodynes include rotorcraft, airplanes, gliders, and several other varieties of aircraft.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Airplanes use wings, or airfoils, to direct the airflow to produce lift.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Wings are usually constructed with a wooden or metal inner framework, and a skin stretched over it.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Rotorcraft use a rotor which acts like a rotating wing, allowing them to hover in place.
[src:tonne/aircraft] When aerodynes carry a payload, it is usually carried inside the aircraft's fuselage, or central structure, but aerodynes can also carry loads attached outside the aircraft or inside the wing.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Unlike aerostats, which control their altitude by changing their weight, aerodynes use control surfaces to control their altitude, or raise or lower the lift on their wing by adjusting their speed.
[src:tonne/aircraft] As they typically travel at higher speeds than aerostats, most aerodynes have a rigid structure consisting of a frame covered by a skin.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Powered aircraft are typically powered by internal combustion engines (piston or turbine) burning fossil fuels—typically gasoline (avgas) or jet fuel.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A very few are powered by rocket power, ramjet propulsion, or by electric motors, or by internal combustion engines of other types, or using other fuels.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A very few have been powered, for short flights, by human muscle energy (e.g.: Gossamer Condor).
[src:tonne/aircraft] The avionics comprise any *electronic* aircraft flight control systems and related equipment, including electronic cockpit instrumentation, navigation, radar, monitoring, and communications systems.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The flight envelope of an aircraft refers to its approved design capabilities in terms of airspeed, load factor and altitude.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The maximal total *range* is the maximum distance an aircraft can fly between takeoff and landing.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Powered aircraft range is limited by the aviation fuel energy storage capacity (chemical or electrical) considering both weight and volume limits.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Unpowered aircraft range depends on factors such as cross-country speed and environmental conditions.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The range can be seen as the cross-country ground speed multiplied by the maximum time in the air.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The fuel time limit for powered aircraft is fixed by the available fuel (considering reserve fuel requirements) and the rate of consumption.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The Airbus A350-900ULR is among the longest range airliners.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Some aircraft can gain energy while airborne through the environment (e.g. collecting solar energy or through rising air currents from mechanical or thermal lifting) or from in-flight refueling.
[src:tonne/aircraft] These aircraft could theoretically have an infinite range.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Control systems adjust the orientation of a vehicle about its CG.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A control system includes control surfaces which, when deflected, generate a moment (or couple from ailerons) about the cg which rotates the aircraft in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:tonne/aircraft] For example, a pitching moment comes from a force applied at a distance forward or aft of the cg, causing the aircraft to pitch up or down.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A fixed-wing aircraft increases or decreases the lift generated by the wings when it pitches nose up or down by increasing or decreasing the angle of attack (AOA).
[src:tonne/aircraft] The roll angle is also known as bank angle on a fixed-wing aircraft, which usually "banks" to change the horizontal direction of flight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A fixed wing is typically unstable in pitch, roll, and yaw.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Pitch and yaw stabilities of conventional fixed wing designs require horizontal and vertical stabilisers, which act similarly to the feathers on an arrow.
[src:tonne/aircraft] These stabilizing surfaces allow equilibrium of aerodynamic forces and to stabilise the flight dynamics of pitch and yaw.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In fixed-wing aircraft, multiple control surfaces are used to adjust the aircraft's roll, pitch, and yaw.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Ailerons, hinged surfaces normally located on the rear edge of the wing, can raise or lower the lift produced by one side of the wing, causing the aircraft to bank to one side.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Elevators, usually located in the horizontal stabilizer, are used to increase or decrease the lift produced by the tail, causing the aircraft to pitch upwards or downwards, which in turn affects the lift of the wing.
[src:tonne/aircraft] However, when the ailerons are used to turn an aircraft to the left, the right aileron must be tilted downwards, producing more drag than the left aileron and causing the aircraft to yaw right.
[src:tonne/aircraft] To counteract this force, most fixed-wing aircraft have a rudder mounted on the vertical stabilizer which can deflect the airflow to the tail left or right to control the aircraft's yaw.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In rotorcraft, control is mainly accomplished through the cyclical tilting of the rotor's blades, increasing the angle of attack of the blades on one side and decreasing the angle of attack on the other.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Similarly to the rudder on fixed-wing aircraft, rotorcraft with powered rotors have a tail rotor, which counters the rotational thrust produced by the rotor and allows the aircraft to turn in forward flight.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Rotorcraft with unpowered rotors, such as autogyros, use a rudder for yaw.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aircraft engines produce gases, noise, and particulates from fossil fuel combustion, raising environmental concerns over their global effects and on local air quality.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Jet airliners contribute to climate change by emitting carbon dioxide (CO2), the best understood greenhouse gas, and, with less scientific understanding, nitrogen oxides, contrails and particulates.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Their radiative forcing is estimated at 1.4 that of CO2 alone, excluding induced cirrus cloud with a very low level of scientific understanding.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In 2018, global commercial operations generated 2.4% of CO2 emissions.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Jet airliners have become more fuel efficient and CO2 emissions per revenue ton-kilometer (RTK) in 2018 were 47% of those in 1990.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In 2018, CO2 emissions averaged 88 grams of CO2 per revenue passenger per km.
[src:tonne/aircraft] While the aviation industry is more fuel efficient, overall emissions have risen as the volume of air travel has increased.
[src:tonne/aircraft] By 2020, aviation emissions were 70% higher than in 2005 and they could grow by 300% by 2050.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aircraft noise pollution disrupts sleep, children's education and could increase cardiovascular risk.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Airports can generate water pollution due to their extensive handling of jet fuel and deicing chemicals if not contained, contaminating nearby water bodies.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aviation activities emit ozone and ultrafine particles, both of which are health hazards.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Piston engines used in general aviation burn Avgas, releasing toxic lead.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aviation's environmental footprint can be reduced by better fuel economy in aircraft, or air traffic control and flight routes can be optimized to lower non-CO2 effects on climate from NOx, particulates or contrails.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aviation biofuel, emissions trading and carbon offsetting, part of the ICAO's CORSIA, can lower CO2 emissions.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Aviation usage can be lowered by short-haul flight bans, train connections, personal choices and aviation taxation and subsidies.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Fuel-powered aircraft may be replaced by hybrid electric aircraft and electric aircraft or by hydrogen-powered aircraft.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Since 2021, the IATA members plan to achieve net-zero carbon emissions by 2050, followed by the ICAO in 2022.
[src:tonne/aircraft] A military aircraft is any aircraft that is operated by a legal or insurrectionary armed service of any type.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Although scheduled air transport is the larger operation in terms of passenger numbers, GA is larger in the number of flights (and flight hours, in the U.S.) In the U.S., GA carries 166 million passengers each year, more than any individual airline, though less than all the airlines combined.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Since 2004, the U.S. airlines combined have carried over 600 million passengers each year, and in 2014, they carried a combined 662,819,232 passengers.
[src:tonne/aircraft] All scheduled air transport is commercial, but general aviation can be either commercial or private.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Normally, the pilot, aircraft, and operator must all be authorized to perform commercial operations through separate commercial licensing, registration, and operation certificates.
[src:tonne/aircraft] An *experimental aircraft* is an aircraft intended for testing new aerospace technologies and design concepts.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The term *research aircraft* or *testbed aircraft*, by contrast, generally denotes aircraft modified to perform scientific studies, such as weather research or geophysical surveying, similar to a research vessel.
[src:tonne/aircraft] The term "experimental aircraft" also has specific legal meaning in Australia, the United States and some other countries; usually used to refer to aircraft flown with an experimental certificate.
[src:tonne/aircraft] In the United States, this also includes most homebuilt aircraft, many of which are based on conventional designs and hence are experimental only in name because of certain restrictions in operation.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Model aircraft are typically small-scale replicas of flying aircraft, or new designs built smaller than most passenger aircraft.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Static model aircraft, which cannot fly, are usually not considered to be aircraft, but they can be used to test aspects of a flying aircraft, such as its aerodynamics.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Flying models are commonly propelled by electric motors, combustion engines, or are gliders, but there are many alternate methods of propulsion, such as wound rubber bands and small jet engines.
[src:tonne/aircraft] Most flying model aircraft are either radio-controlled aircraft, fly freely, or are controlled by wires held by the pilot.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] A **base unit of measurement** (also referred to as a **base unit** or **fundamental unit**) is a unit of measurement adopted for a *base quantity*.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] A base quantity is one of a conventionally chosen subset of physical quantities, where no quantity in the subset can be expressed in terms of the others.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] The SI base units, or *Systéme International d'unités*, consists of the metre, kilogram, second, ampere, kelvin, mole and candela.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] A **unit multiple** (or **multiple of a unit**) is an integer multiple of a given unit; likewise a **unit submultiple** (or **submultiple of a unit**) is a submultiple or a unit fraction of a given unit.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] *Unit prefixes* are common base-10 or base-2 powers multiples and submultiples of units.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] While a base unit is one that has been explicitly so designated, a **derived unit** is unit for a *derived quantity*, involving the combination of quantities with different units; several *SI derived units* are specially named.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] A *coherent derived unit* involves no conversion factors.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] In the language of measurement, *physical quantities* are quantifiable aspects of the world, such as time, distance, velocity, mass, temperature, energy, and weight, and *units* are used to describe their magnitude or quantity.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Many of these quantities are related to each other by various physical laws, and as a result the units of a quantities can be generally be expressed as a product of powers of other units; for example, momentum is mass multiplied by velocity, while velocity is distance divided by time.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] These relationships are discussed in dimensional analysis.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Those that can be expressed in this fashion in terms of the base units are called derived units.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] In the International System of Units (SI), there are seven base units: kilogram, metre, candela, second, ampere, kelvin, and mole.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Several derived units have been defined, many with special names and symbols.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] In 2019 the seven SI base units were redefined in terms of seven defining constants.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Therefore, the SI base units are no longer strictly necessary but were retained both for historical and practical reasons.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] A set of base dimensions of quantity is a minimal set of units such that every physical quantity can be expressed in terms of this set.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] The traditional base dimensions are mass, length, time, charge, and temperature, but in principle, other base quantities could be used.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Electric current could be used instead of charge or speed could be used instead of length.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Some physicists have not recognized temperature as a base dimension since it simply expresses the energy per particle per degree of freedom which can be expressed in terms of energy (or mass, length, and time).
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Duff argues that only dimensionless values have physical meaning and all dimensional units are human constructs.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] The ontological issue is whether these fundamental constants really exist as dimensional or dimensionless quantities.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] For instance, time and distance are related to each other by the speed of light, *c*, which is a fundamental constant.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] It is possible to use this relationship to eliminate either the base unit of time or that of distance.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Similar considerations apply to the Planck constant, *h*, which relates energy (with dimension expressible in terms of mass, length and time) to frequency (with dimension expressible in terms of time).
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] In theoretical physics it is customary to use such units (natural units) in which *c* = 1 and *ħ* = 1.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] A similar choice can be applied to the vacuum permittivity, *ε*0.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] The preferred choices vary by the field in physics.
[src:tonne/base-unit-of-measurement] Using natural units leaves every physical quantity expressed as a dimensionless number, which is noted by physicists disputing the existence of incompatible base quantities.
[src:tonne/calorie] The **calorie** is a unit of energy that originated from the caloric theory of heat.
[src:tonne/calorie] The **small calorie** or **gram calorie** is defined as the amount of heat needed to raise the temperature of one milliliter of water by one degree Celsius (or one kelvin).
[src:tonne/calorie] In the US, "large calorie" is also used to mean kilocalorie (1 kcal = 1000 cal) .
[src:tonne/calorie] In nutrition and food science, the term *calorie* and the symbol *cal* may refer to the large unit or to the small unit in different regions of the world.
[src:tonne/calorie] It is generally used in publications and package labels to express the energy value of foods in per serving or per weight, recommended dietary caloric intake, metabolic rates, etc.
[src:tonne/calorie] Some authors recommend the spelling *Calorie* and the symbol *Cal* (both with a capital C) if the large calorie is meant, to avoid confusion; however, this convention is often ignored.
[src:tonne/calorie] In physics and chemistry, the word *calorie* and its symbol usually refer to the small unit, the large one being called *kilocalorie* (kcal).
[src:tonne/calorie] However, the calorie is not part of the International System of Units (SI) and is regarded as obsolete, having been replaced by the SI derived unit of energy, the joule (J), or the kilojoule (kJ) for 1,000 joules.
[src:tonne/calorie] The precise equivalence between calories and joules has varied over the years, but in thermochemistry and nutrition it is now generally assumed that one (small) calorie (**thermochemical calorie**) is equal to exactly 4.184 J, and therefore one kilocalorie (one large calorie) is 4184 J or 4.184 kJ.
[src:tonne/calorie] The term "calorie" comes from Latin *calor* 'heat'.
[src:tonne/calorie] It was first introduced by Nicolas Clément, as a unit of heat energy, in lectures on experimental calorimetry during the years 1819–1824.
[src:tonne/calorie] The term (written with lowercase "c") entered French and English dictionaries between 1841 and 1867.
[src:tonne/calorie] The same term was used for the "small" unit by Pierre Antoine Favre (chemist) and Jean Thiébault Silbermann (physicist) in 1852.
[src:tonne/calorie] In 1879, Marcellin Berthelot distinguished between gram-calorie and kilogram-calorie, and proposed using "Calorie", with capital "C", for the large unit.
[src:tonne/calorie] This usage was adopted by Wilbur Olin Atwater, a professor at Wesleyan University, in 1887, in an influential article on the energy content of food.
[src:tonne/calorie] The smaller unit was used by U.S. physician Joseph Howard Raymond, in his 1894 textbook *A Manual of Human Physiology*.
[src:tonne/calorie] He proposed calling the "large" unit "kilocalorie", but the term did not catch on until some years later.
[src:tonne/calorie] The small calorie (cal) was recognized as a unit of the CGS system in 1896, alongside the already-existing CGS unit of energy, the erg (first suggested by Clausius in 1864, under the name *ergon*, and officially adopted in 1882).
[src:tonne/calorie] In 1928, there were already serious complaints about the possible confusion arising from the two main definitions of the calorie and whether the notion of using the capital letter to distinguish them was sound.
[src:tonne/calorie] The joule was the officially adopted SI unit of energy at the ninth General Conference on Weights and Measures in 1948.
[src:tonne/calorie] The calorie was mentioned in the 7th edition of the SI brochure as an example of a non-SI unit.
[src:tonne/calorie] The alternate spelling calory is a less-common, non-standard variant.
[src:tonne/calorie] The "small" calorie is broadly defined as the amount of energy needed to increase the temperature of 1 gram of water by 1 °C (or 1 K, which is the same increment, a gradation of one percent of the interval between the melting point and the boiling point of water).
[src:tonne/calorie] The actual amount of energy required to accomplish this temperature increase depends on the atmospheric pressure and the starting temperature; different choices of these parameters have resulted in several different precise definitions of the unit.
[src:tonne/calorie] The standard atmospheric pressure can be taken to be 101.325 kPa.
[src:tonne/calorie] The figure depends on the conversion factor between "international joules" and "absolute" (modern, SI) joules.
[src:tonne/calorie] The two definitions most common in older literature appear to be the *15 °C calorie* and the *thermochemical calorie*.
[src:tonne/calorie] Until 1948, the latter was defined as 4.1833 international joules; the current standard of 4.184 J was chosen to have the new thermochemical calorie represent the same quantity of energy as before.
[src:tonne/calorie] In North America, in a nutritional context, the "large" unit is used almost exclusively.
[src:tonne/calorie] It is generally written "calorie" with lowercase "c" and symbol "cal", even in government publications.
[src:tonne/calorie] The SI unit kilojoule (kJ) may be used instead, in legal or scientific contexts.
[src:tonne/calorie] Most American nutritionists prefer the unit kilocalorie to the unit kilojoules, whereas most physiologists prefer to use kilojoules.
[src:tonne/calorie] In the majority of other countries, nutritionists prefer the kilojoule to the kilocalorie.
[src:tonne/calorie] In Europe, on nutrition facts labels, energy is expressed in both kilojoules and kilocalories, abbreviated as "kJ" and "kcal" respectively.
[src:tonne/calorie] The unit is most commonly used to express food energy, namely the specific energy (energy per mass) of metabolizing different types of food.
[src:tonne/calorie] For example, fat (triglyceride lipids) contains 9 kilocalories per gram (kcal/g), while carbohydrates (sugar and starch) and protein contain approximately 4 kcal/g.
[src:tonne/calorie] The "large" unit is also used to express recommended nutritional intake or consumption, as in "calories per day".
[src:tonne/calorie] Dieting is the practice of eating food in a regulated way to decrease, maintain, or increase body weight, or to prevent and treat diseases such as diabetes and obesity.
[src:tonne/calorie] As weight loss depends on reducing caloric intake, different kinds of calorie-reduced diets have been shown to be generally effective.
[src:tonne/calorie] In other scientific contexts, the term "calorie" and the symbol "cal" almost always refers to the small unit; the "large" unit being generally called "kilocalorie" with symbol "kcal".
[src:tonne/calorie] It is mostly used to express the amount of energy released in a chemical reaction or phase change, typically per mole of substance, as in kilocalories per mole.
[src:tonne/calorie] It is also occasionally used to specify other energy quantities that relate to reaction energy, such as enthalpy of formation and the size of activation barriers.
[src:tonne/calorie] However, it is increasingly being superseded by the SI unit, the joule (J); and metric multiples thereof, such as the kilojoule (kJ).
[src:tonne/calorie] However, this estimate assumes that the volumetric heat capacity of the solution is 1 kcal/(L⋅K), which is not exact even for pure water.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] While Canadian English tends to be close to American English in most regards, classifiable together as North American English, Canadian English also possesses elements from British English as well as some uniquely Canadian characteristics.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The precise influence of American English, British English, and other sources on Canadian English varieties has been the ongoing focus of systematic studies since the 1950s.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Standard Canadian and General American English share identical or near-identical phonemic inventories, though their exact phonetic realizations may sometimes differ.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Accent differences can also be heard between those who live in urban centres versus those living in rural settings.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadians and Americans themselves often have trouble differentiating their own two accents, particularly since Standard Canadian and Western United States English have both been undergoing the Low-Back-Merger Shift since the 1980s.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian English as an academic field of inquiry solidified around the time of the Second World War.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] While early linguistic approaches date back to the second half of the 19th century, the first textbook to consider Canadian English in one form or another was not published until 1940.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Avis was its most forceful spokesperson after the Second World War until the 1970s.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] His team of lexicographers managed to date the term "Canadian English" to a speech by a Scottish Presbyterian minister, the Reverend Archibald Constable Geikie, in an address to the Canadian Institute in 1857.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Geikie, a Scottish-born Canadian, reflected the Anglocentric attitude that would be prevalent in Canada for the next hundred years when he referred to the language as "a corrupt dialect", in comparison with what he considered the proper English spoken by immigrants from Britain.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] One of the earliest influences on Canadian English was the French language, which was brought to Canada by the French colonists in the 17th century.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] French words and expressions were adopted into Canadian English, especially in the areas of cuisine, politics, and social life.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] For example, words like *poutine* and *toque* are uniquely Canadian French terms that have become part of the Canadian English lexicon.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] An important influence on Canadian English was British English, which was brought to Canada by British settlers in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian English borrowed many words and expressions from British English, including words like *lorry*, *flat*, and *lift*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] However, Canadian English also developed its own unique vocabulary, including words like *toque*, *chesterfield*, and *double-double*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In the early 20th century, western Canada was largely populated by farmers from Central and Eastern Europe who were not anglophones.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] At the time, most anglophones there were re-settlers from Ontario or Quebec who had British, Irish, or Loyalist ancestry, or some mixture of these.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the prairies underwent anglicization and linguistic homogenization through education and exposure to Canadian and American media.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] American English also had a significant impact on the origins of Canadian English as well as again in the 20th century and since then as a result of increased cultural and economic ties between the two countries.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] American English terms like gasoline, truck, and apartment are commonly used in Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The growth of Canadian media, including television, film, and literature, has also played a role in shaping Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Chambers (1998) notes that Canadian media has helped to create new words and expressions that reflect Canadian culture and values.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian institutions, such as the CBC and the Canadian Oxford Dictionary, have also played a role in promoting and defining Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In addition to these influences, Canadian English has also been minorly shaped by Indigenous languages.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Indigenous words such as *moose*, *toboggan*, *kayak*, *skookum*, and *moccasin* have become part of the Canadian English lexicon.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian English is the product of five waves of immigration and settlement over a period of more than two centuries.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian English has been developing features of its own since the early 19th century.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The second wave from Britain and Ireland was encouraged to settle in Canada after the War of 1812 by the governors of Canada, who were worried about American dominance and influence among its citizens.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Further waves of immigration from around the globe peaking in 1910, 1960, and at the present time had a lesser influence, but they did make Canada a multicultural country, ready to accept linguistic change from around the world during the current period of globalization.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The languages of Aboriginal peoples in Canada started to influence European languages used in Canada even before widespread settlement took place, and the French of Lower Canada provided vocabulary, with words such as *tuque* and *portage*, to the English of Upper Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Overall, the history of Canadian English is a reflection of the country's diverse linguistic and cultural heritage.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] While Canadian English has borrowed many words and expressions from other languages, it has also developed its own unique vocabulary and pronunciation that reflects the country's distinct identity.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Studies on earlier forms of English in Canada are rare.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] An overview of diachronic work on Canadian English, or diachronically relevant work, is Dollinger.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Until the 2000s, basically all commentators on the history of CanE have argued from the "language-external" history, i.e. social and political history.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] An exception has been in the area of lexis, where Avis *et al.*'s 1967 *Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles* offered real-time historical data through its quotations.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Starting in the 2000s, historical linguists have started to study earlier Canadian English with historical linguistic data.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Most notably, Dollinger (2008) pioneered the historical corpus linguistic approach for English in Canada with CONTE (Corpus of Early Ontario English, 1776–1849) and offers a developmental scenario for 18th- and 19th-century Ontario.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Historically, Canadian English included a class-based sociolect known as *Canadian dainty*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Treated as a marker of upper-class prestige in the 19th and early 20th centuries, Canadian dainty was marked by the use of some features of British English pronunciation, resulting in an accent similar, but not identical, to the Mid-Atlantic accent known in the United States.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] This accent faded in prominence following World War II, when it became stigmatized as pretentious, and is now rare.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The Governor General Vincent Massey, the writer and broadcaster Peter Stursberg, the actor Lorne Greene, and the actor Christopher Plummer are examples of men who were raised in Canada but spoke with a British-influenced accent.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian spelling of the English language combines British and American conventions, the two dominant varieties, and adds some domestic idiosyncrasies.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] For many words, American and British spelling are both acceptable.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Spelling in Canadian English co-varies with regional and social variables, somewhat more so, perhaps, than in the two dominant varieties of English, yet general trends have emerged since the 1970s.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian spelling conventions can be partly explained by Canada's trade history.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canada's political history has also had an influence on Canadian spelling.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Macdonald, once advised the Governor General of Canada to issue an order-in-council directing that government papers be written in the British style.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] A contemporary reference for formal Canadian spelling is the spelling used for Hansard transcripts of the Parliament of Canada .
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Many Canadian editors, though, use the *Canadian Oxford Dictionary*, often along with the chapter on spelling in *Editing Canadian English*, and, where necessary (depending on context), one or more other references.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Throughout part of the 20th century, some Canadian newspapers adopted American spellings, for example, *color* as opposed to the British-based *colour*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Some of the most substantial historical spelling data can be found in Dollinger (2010) and Grue (2013).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The use of such spellings was the long-standing practice of the Canadian Press perhaps since that news agency's inception, but visibly the norm prior to World War II.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The practice of dropping the letter *u* in such words was also considered a labour-saving technique during the early days of printing in which movable type was set manually.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian newspapers also received much of their international content from American press agencies, so it was much easier for editorial staff to leave the spellings from the wire services as provided.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In the 1990s, Canadian newspapers began to adopt the British spelling variants such as *-our* endings, notably with *The Globe and Mail* changing its spelling policy in October 1990.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Other Canadian newspapers adopted similar changes later that decade, such as the Southam newspaper chain's conversion in September 1998.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The *Toronto Star* adopted this new spelling policy in September 1997 after that publication's ombudsman discounted the issue earlier in 1997.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The *Star* had always avoided using recognized Canadian spelling, citing the *Gage Canadian Dictionary* in their defence.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Controversy around this issue was frequent.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] When the *Gage Dictionary* finally adopted standard Canadian spelling, the *Star* followed suit.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] *Maclean's*, continue to prefer American spellings.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The first series of dictionaries of Canadian English was published by Gage Ltd. under the chief-editorships of Charles J.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Avis as of 1960 and the "Big Six" editors plus Faith Avis.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The *Beginner's Dictionary* (1962), the *Intermediate Dictionary* (1964) and, finally, the *Senior Dictionary* (1967) were milestones in Canadian English lexicography.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In November 1967 *A Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles* (DCHP) was published and completed the first edition of Gage's Dictionary of Canadian English Series.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The DCHP documents the historical development of Canadian English words that can be classified as "Canadianisms".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] It therefore includes words such as mukluk, Canuck, and bluff, but does not list common core words such as desk, table or car.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Many secondary schools in Canada use the graded dictionaries.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The dictionaries have regularly been updated since: the *Senior Dictionary,* edited by Robert John Gregg, was renamed *Gage Canadian Dictionary*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Its fifth edition was printed beginning in 1997.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Gage was acquired by Thomson Nelson around 2003.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The latest editions were published in 2009 by HarperCollins.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] On 17 March 2017 a second edition of DCHP, the online Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles 2 (DCHP-2), was published.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] 1 300 novel meanings or 1 002 lexemes to the documented lexicon of Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In 1998, Oxford University Press produced a Canadian English dictionary, after five years of lexicographical research, entitled *The Oxford Canadian Dictionary*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] A second edition, retitled *The Canadian Oxford Dictionary*, was published in 2004.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Just as the older dictionaries it includes uniquely Canadian words and words borrowed from other languages, and surveyed spellings, such as whether *colour* or *color* was the more popular choice in common use.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Paperback and concise versions (2005, 2006), with minor updates, are available.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Since 2022, the Editors' Association of Canada has been leading the writing of a new *Canadian English Dictionary* within a national dictionary Consortium.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The Consortium comprises the Editors' Association of Canada, the UBC Canadian English Lab, and Queen's University's Strategy Language Unit.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian raising is when the onsets of diphthongs /aɪ/ and /aʊ/ get raised to [ə] or [ʌ] before voiceless segments.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] There are areas in the eastern U.S. where some words are pronounced with Canadian raising.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Some young Canadians may show Goose-fronting.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] U.S. southern dialects have long had goose-fronting, but this goose-fronting among young Canadians and Californians is more recent.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Some young Californians also show signs of the Low-Back-Merger Shift.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The cot-caught merger is perhaps not general in the U.S., but younger speakers seem more likely to have it.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In terms of the major sound systems (phonologies) of English around the world, Canadian English aligns most closely to American English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Some dialectologists group Canadian and American English together under a common North American English sound system.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The mainstream Canadian accent ("Standard Canadian") is often compared to the General American accent, a middle ground lacking in noticeable regional features.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Western Canada (British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, Manitoba) shows the largest dialect diversity.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Northern Canada is, according to William Labov, a dialect region in formation where a homogeneous English dialect has not yet formed.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Labov's research focused on urban areas, and did not survey the country, but they found similarities among the English spoken in Ottawa, Toronto, Calgary, Edmonton and Vancouver.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Standard Canadian English is socially defined.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] It is spoken by those who live in urban Canada, in a middle-class job (or one of their parents holds such employment), who are second generation or later (born and raised in Canada) and speak English as (one of their) dominant language(s) (Dollinger 2019a, adapted from Chambers 1998).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] It is the variety spoken, in Chambers' (1998: 252) definition, by Anglophone or multilingual residents, who are second generation or later (i.e. born in Canada) and who live in urban settings.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] 36% of the Canadian population speak Standard Canadian English in the 2006 population, with 38% in the 2011 census.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The literature has for a long time conflated the notions of Standard Canadian English (StCE) and regional variation.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] While some regional dialects are close to Standard Canadian English, they are not identical to it.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] To the untrained ear, for instance, a BC middle-class speaker from a rural setting may seemingly be speaking Standard Canadian English, but, given Chambers' definition, such a person, because of the rural provenance, would not be included in the accepted definition (see the previous section).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The *Atlas of North American English*, while being the best source for US regional variation, is not a good source for Canadian regional variation, as its analysis is based on only 33 Canadian speakers.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Boberg's studies offer the best data for the delimitation of dialect zones.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The results for vocabulary and phonetics overlap to a great extent, which has allowed the proposal of dialect zones.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The words *Aboriginal* and *Indigenous* are capitalized when used in a Canadian context.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] First Nations and Inuit from Northern Canada speak a version of Canadian English influenced by the phonology of their first languages.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Non-indigenous Canadians in these regions are relatively recent arrivals, and have not produced a dialect that is distinct from southern Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Overall, First Nations Canada English dialects rest between language loss and language revitalization.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] British Columbia has the greatest linguistic diversity, as it is home to about half of the Indigenous languages spoken in Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Most of the languages spoken in the province are endangered due to the small number of speakers.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] To some extent, the dialects reflect the historical contexts where English has been a major colonizing language.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The dialects are also a result of the late stages of depidginization and decreolization, which resulted in linguistic markers of Indigenous identity and solidarity.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] These dialects are observed to have developed a lingua franca due to the contact between English and Indigenous populations, and eventually, the various dialects began to converge with standard English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Certain First Nations English have also shown to have phonological standard Canadian English, thus resulting in a more distinct dialect formation.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Plains Cree, for instance, is a language that has less phonological contrasts compared to standard Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The stops /p/, /t/, and /k/ are mostly voiceless and unaspirated, though they may vary in other phonetic environments from voiceless to voiced.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Plains Cree also does not have the liquids or fricatives found in the standard form.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Dene Suline, on the other hand, has more phonological contrasts, resulting in the use of features not seen in the standard form.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The language has 39 phonemic consonants and a higher proportion of glottalized consonants.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Many in the Maritime provinces – Nova Scotia, New Brunswick and Prince Edward Island – have an accent that sounds more like Scottish English and, in some places, Irish English than General American.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Outside of major communities, dialects can vary markedly from community to community, as well as from province to province, reflecting ethnic origin as well as a past in which there were few roads and many communities, with some isolated villages.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Into the 1980s, residents of villages in northern Nova Scotia could identify themselves by dialects and accents distinctive to their village.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The dialects of Prince Edward Island are often considered the most distinct grouping.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Although it has not been studied extensively, the speech of Cape Breton specifically seems to bear many similarities with the nearby island of Newfoundland, which is often why Westerners can have a hard time differentiating the two accents.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] For instance, they both use the fronting of the low back vowel.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] These similarities can be attributed to geographic proximity, the fact that about one-quarter of the Cape Breton population descends from Irish immigrants (many of whom arrived via Newfoundland) and the Scottish and Irish influences on both provinces.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The speech of Cape Breton can almost be seen as a continuum between the two extremes of the Halifax variant and the Newfoundland variant.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In addition, there is heavy influence of standard varieties of Canadian English on Cape Breton English, especially in the diphthongization of the goat and goose vowels and the frequent use of Canadian raising.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Compared to the commonly spoken English dominating neighbouring provinces, Newfoundland English is famously distinct in its dialects and accents.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Newfoundland English differs in vowel pronunciation, morphology, syntax, and preservation of archaic adverbial-intensifiers.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The dialect varies markedly from community to community, as well as from region to region.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Its distinctiveness partly results from a European settlement history that dates back centuries, which explains Newfoundland's most notable linguistic regions: an Irish-settled area in the southeast (the southern Avalon Peninsula) and an English-settled area in the southwest.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] A well-known phonetic feature many Newfoundland speakers possess is the kit-dress merger.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The mid lax /ɛ/ here is raised to the high lax stressed /ɪ/, particularly before oral stops and nasals, so consequently "pen" is pronounced more like "pin".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Another phonetic feature more unique to Newfoundland English is TH-stopping.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Here, the voiceless dental fricative /θ/ in words like *myth* and *width* are pronounced more like *t* or the voiced dental fricative /ð/ in words like *the* and *these*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] TH-stopping is more common for /ð/, especially in unstressed function words (e.g. that, those, their, etc.).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian raising is quite strong throughout the province of Ontario, except within the Ottawa Valley.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The introduction of Canadian raising to Canada can be attributed to the Scottish and Irish immigrants who arrived in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The origins of Canadian raising to Scotland and revealed that the Scottish dialects spoken by these immigrants had a probable impact on its development.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] This feature impacts the pronunciation of the /aɪ/ sound in "right" and the /aʊ/ sound in "lout".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Canadian Raising indicates a scenario where the start of the diphthong is nearer to the destination of the glide before voiceless consonants than before voiced consonants.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The Canadian Shift is also a common vowel shift found in Ontario.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The retraction of /æ/ was found to be more advanced for women in Ontario than for people from the Prairies or Atlantic Canada and men.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In the southern part of Southwestern Ontario (roughly in the line south from Sarnia to St.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Thus, a strong accent similar to Central Ontarian is heard, yet many different phrasings exist.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] It is typical in the area to drop phonetic sounds to make shorter contractions, such as: *prolly* (probably), *goin'* (going), and "Wuts goin' on tonight?
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] D'ya wanna do sumthin'?" It is particularly strong in the County of Bruce, so much that it is commonly referred to as being the Bruce Cownian (Bruce Countian) accent.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Also, /ɜr/ merge with /ɛr/ to [ɛɹ], with "were" sounding more like "wear".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Residents of the Golden Horseshoe (including the Greater Toronto Area) are known to merge the second /t/ with the /n/ in *Toronto*, pronouncing the name variously as [təˈɹɒɾ̃o] or [ˈtɹɒɾ̃o].
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] This is not unique to Toronto; Atlanta is often pronounced "Atlanna" by residents.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Sometimes /ð/ is elided altogether, resulting in "Do you want this one er'iss one?" The word *southern* is often pronounced with [aʊ].
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In the area north of the Regional Municipality of York and south of Parry Sound, notably among those who were born in the surrounding communities, the cutting down of syllables and consonants often heard, e.g.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] "probably" is reduced to "prolly" or "probly" when used as a response.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In Greater Toronto, the diphthong tends to be fronted (as a result the word *about* is pronounced as [əˈbɛʊt]).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The Greater Toronto Area is linguistically diverse, with 43 percent of its people having a mother tongue other than English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] As a result Toronto English has distinctly more variability than Inland Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In Eastern Ontario, Canadian raising is not as strong as it is in the rest of the province.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In Prescott and Russell, parts of Stormont-Dundas-Glengarry and Eastern Ottawa, French accents are often mixed with English ones due to the high Franco-Ontarian population there.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In Lanark County, Western Ottawa and Leeds-Grenville and the rest of Stormont-Dundas-Glengarry, the accent spoken is nearly identical to that spoken in Central Ontario and the Quinte area.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] A linguistic enclave has also formed in the Ottawa Valley, heavily influenced by original Scottish, Irish, and German settlers, and existing along the Ontario-Quebec boundary, which has its own distinct accent known as the Ottawa Valley twang (or brogue).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Phonetically, the Ottawa Valley twang is characterized by the lack of Canadian raising as well as the cot–caught merger, two common elements of mainstream Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] This accent is quite rare in the region today.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] English is a minority language in Quebec (with French the majority), but has many speakers in Montreal, the Eastern Townships and in the Gatineau-Ottawa region.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] A person whose mother tongue is English and who still speaks English is called an *Anglophone*, versus a *Francophone*, or French speaker.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Many people in Montreal distinguish between words like *marry* versus *merry* and *parish* versus *perish*, which are homophones to most other speakers of Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Quebec Anglophones generally pronounce French street names in Montreal as French words, for example, *Pie IX* Boulevard is pronounced as in French: not as "pie nine" but as /ˌpiːˈnʊf/ *pee-NUUF* (compare French [pi.nœf]).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] On the other hand, Anglophones pronounce the final *d* as in *Bernard* and *Bouchard*; the word *Montreal* is pronounced as an English word and *Rue Lambert-Closse* is known as *Clossy Street* (vs French [klɔs]).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In certain areas of Montreal, especially in some of the western suburbs like Côte-St-Luc and Hampstead, there is a strong Jewish influence.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] A large wave of Jewish immigration from Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union before and after World War II is also evident today.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Their English has a strong Yiddish influence, and there are some similarities to English spoken in New York.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Western Canadian English describes the English spoken in the four most western provinces—British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] British Columbia, in particular is a sub-zone on the lexical level.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Phonetically, Western Canadian English has much more /æɡ/ raising and much less /æn/ than further east, and Canadian raised /aʊ/ is further back.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] British Columbia English shares dialect features with both Standard Canadian English and the American Pacific Northwest English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] In the past, the ANAE reported that Vancouverites' participation in the Canadian raising of /aɪ/ was questionable, but nowadays they tend to raise both /aɪ/ and /aʊ/.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The "o" in such words as *holy, goal, load, know,* etc. is pronounced as a close-mid back rounded vowel, [o], but not as rounded as in the Prairies where there are strong Scandinavian, Slavic and German influences, which can lend to a more stereotypical "Canadian" accent.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Finally, similarly to the prince-prints merger, there is also the /t/ sound which according to Gregg (2016), "with many [Vancouver] speakers [is] intrusive between /l/ or /n/ and /s/ in words like sense /sɛnts/, Wilson /wɪltsən/ [and] also /'ɒltsoʊ/ " .
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] English in Saskatchewan has its pool of phonetic features shared with other provinces used by certain demographics.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] For instance, it has the consonant variables /ntV/ and /VtV/, the latter being a common feature of North American English and is defined as the intervoicing of /t/ between vowels.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Meanwhile, /ntV/ "frequently occurs in words such as "centre" and "twenty" where /t/ follows the alveolar nasal /n/ and precedes an unstressed vowel".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] According to Nylvek (1992), both variables of /t/ are generally more often used by younger male over older female speakers.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] There are a handful of syntactical practices unique to Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] When writing, Canadians may start a sentence with *As well*, in the sense of "in addition"; this construction is a Canadianism.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] North American English prefers *have got* to *have* to denote possession or obligation (as in *I've got a car* vs.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] *I have a car*); Canadian English differs from American English in tending to eschew plain *got* (*I got a car*), which is a common third option in informal US English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The grammatical construction "*be done* something" means roughly "*have/has finished* something".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] For example, "I am done my homework" and "The dog is done dinner" are genuine sentences in this dialect, respectively meaning "I have finished my homework" and "The dog has finished dinner".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Another example, "Let's start after you're done all the coffee", means "Let's start after you've finished all the coffee".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] This is not exactly the same as the standard construction "*to be done with* something", since "She is done the computer" can only mean "She is done with the computer" in one sense: "She has finished (building) the computer".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Date and time notation in Canadian English is a mixture of British and American practices.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The date can be written in the form of either "July 1, 2017" or "1 July 2017"; the latter is common in more formal writing and bilingual contexts.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The Government of Canada only recommends writing all-numeric dates in the form of YYYY-MM-DD (e.g.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Nonetheless, the traditional DD/MM/YY and MM/DD/YY systems remain in everyday use, which can be interpreted in multiple ways: 01/07/17 can mean either 1 July 2017 or 7 January 2017.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Private members' bills have repeatedly attempted to clarify the situation.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] The government also recommends use of the 24-hour clock, which is widely used in contexts such as transportation schedules, parking meters, and data transmission.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p01] Many English speakers use the 12-hour clock in everyday speech, even when reading from a 24-hour display.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Where Canadian English shares vocabulary with other English dialects, it tends to share most with American English, but also has many non-American terms distinctively shared instead with Britain.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In addition, the vocabulary of Canadian English also features some words that are seldom (if ever) found elsewhere.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A good resource for these and other words is *A Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles*, which is currently being revised at the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] As a member of the Commonwealth of Nations, Canada shares many items of institutional terminology and professional designations with the countries of the former British Empire—for example, *constable*, for a police officer of the lowest rank, and *chartered accountant*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] While Canadian English has vocabulary that distinguishes it from other varieties of English across the world, there is significant regional variation in its lexis within Canada as well.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A balanced cross-continental sample of 1800 Canadians and 360 Americans the Canada and the USA is the result of Boberg's North American Regional Vocabulary Survey (NARVS), a questionnaire employed by Boberg from 1999–2007 that sought out lexical items that vary regionally within Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Six regions were identified in the NARVS data collection: The West, which includes British Columbia and the Prairies; Ontario; Quebec, which represents data from Montreal mostly; New Brunswick and Nova Scotia; Prince Edward Island; and Newfoundland.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Many regional differences in the lexis are item-specific.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] For example, one of these items is the term used to refer to a pizza with all available toppings.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] While Atlantic Canada refers to this order as ‘the works', the majority term used from eastern Ontario to the West Coast is 'deluxe', and terms such as 'all-dressed' and 'everything-on-it' are used in Quebec and Toronto, respectively.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Other examples include the regionally varied usage of 'running shoes'/'runners'/'sneakers' to describe athletic shoes, and 'notebook'/'scribbler'/'cahier' to describe any type of plain note-pad.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Despite the regional variation of vocabulary items within Canada, the lexis of Canadian English still maintains greater commonality between its own regions than it does with American English or British English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Quebec recognizes French as its primary language.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] As a result, English has no official status in Quebec and is not used often in the public sphere.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Although, in more metropolitan areas such as Montreal or Quebec City, it is not uncommon to see English media in public, such as in advertisements and store-fronts.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Also, the provincial government must officially be referred to as the "Gouvernement du Québec", regardless of the language being used by the speaker.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The francophone dominance in Quebec makes the province a linguistic anomaly within Canada, where English maintains a negligible role in government and public domains.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] While the lexical catalog of Quebec English contains items influenced or borrowed from French, the influence of the dominant French language on Quebec English is marginal.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Although Quebec English differs from other Canadian regional lexes due to its special contact with French, it still shares some similarities with the lexis of other Canadian regions.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] For instance, the use of lexical items such as *all-dressed* has been successfully transferred to most other Canadian regional lexes.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Words used mainly in Quebec and especially in Montreal are: *stage* for "apprenticeship" or "internship", *copybook* for a notebook, *dépanneur* or *dep* for a convenience store, and *guichet* for an ABM/ATM.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] It is also common for Anglophones, particularly those of Greek or Italian descent, to use translated French words instead of common English equivalents such as "open" and "close" for "on" and "off" or "Open the lights, please" for "Turn on the lights, please".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Southern Ontario was initially settled by white Protestants, with the late 19th century witnessing the migration of white Protestant settlers from Ontario to western Canada following the suppression of the Métis opposition.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] This migration facilitated the transplantation of the Ontario accent and the emergence of a homogeneous Canadian English dialect.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Distinctive to Ontario are Canadianisms such as concession roads, which refer to roads that transect a township, dew-worm, which refers to an earthworm, and fire-reel, which refers to a fire truck.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Avis identified several linguistic features characteristic of Ontarians, including their preference for the word vacation, rather than holiday—which is considered more British English—and sack over paper bag.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] While there may be numerous such lexical differences in the speech of provincial and national borderers, Avis asserts that these are relatively minor compared to the linguistic features held in common.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Furthermore, Avis suggests that the difference between American English and Ontario English is relatively small near the border due to their close proximity.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The historical settlement patterns of southern Ontario, coupled with linguistic research, indicate the existence of distinctively Ontarian lexical items.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] However, Ontario maintains greater similarities with other Canadian regions than it does with the neighbouring American English and its regional variations.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Northern Ontario English has several distinct qualities stemming from its large Franco-Ontarian population.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] As a result several French and English words are used interchangeably.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A number of phrases and expressions may also be found in Northern Ontario that are not present in the rest of the province, such as the use of *camp* for a summer home where Southern Ontario speakers would idiomatically use cottage.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In the mid to late 90s, certain words from Jamaican Patois, Arabic and Somali were incorporated into the local variety of English by Toronto youth, especially in immigrant communities, thus giving rise to Toronto slang.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] These examples included words such as *mandem*, *styll*, *wallahi*, *wasteman*, and *yute*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The Prairies, consisting of Manitoba, Saskatchewan, and Alberta, have their own lexical features.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The linguistic legacy from the settlement patterns in these regions, along with the Indigenous communities, specifically the large Métis population in Saskatchewan and Manitoba also carry certain linguistic traits inherited from the French, Indigenous, and Celtic forebears.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The linguistic features brought by Ukrainian, German, and Mennonite populations in the Saskatchewan Valley of Saskatchewan and Red River Valley of Manitoba have also influenced the lexis of the Prairies.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Some terms are derived from these groups and some are formed within the region by locals throughout time.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] An example of the former is the high-profile variable bunnyhug, a term for a hooded sweatshirt in Saskatchewan.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] As discussed in The Dictionary of Canadianisms on Historical Principles, bunnyhug is purposely and commonly used by young Saskatchewan speakers to indicate a sense of provincial identity, and is referred to as a Saskatchewanism.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] It should be further noted that it is assumed based on circumstantial evidence that teenagers played a crucial and special role in the spread and adoption of the term bunnyhug for hooded sweatshirts.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Across Saskatchewan, Alberta, and Manitoba there are other terms consistent in or throughout the 3 provinces.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Biffed is a term for falling, such as "John biffed it over there".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Pickerel is Manitoba's official fish, also known as Walleye.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Play structure is used to describe a playground for children consisting of monkey bars, slides, etc.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canada's Atlantic provinces were the first part of North America to be explored by Europeans.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The Atlantic provinces, historically and collectively called the Maritimes, consist of New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Newfoundland and Labrador, which is not part of the Maritimes, is also part of Atlantic Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The historical immigrants from Europe have shaped cultures and lexical catalogs across the regions of Atlantic Canada that reflect British, Scottish, Gaelic, and French customs.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The vernacular variations of English spoken in the Atlantic region of Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Newfoundland and Labrador English (NLE) possesses unique vocabulary compared to standard Canadian English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The Dictionary of Newfoundland English covers the vocabulary common to Newfoundlanders, such as Newfoundland "screech rum", a Newfoundland-specific brand of rum; mummering, referring to a Christmas tradition; and gut-foundered, meaning starving or fastened.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Nova Scotia also is home to its own vocabulary.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The term "Sobeys bag", used to refer to a plastic grocery bag, originates from the Nova Scotian grocery store chain Sobeys.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Similarly, Prince Edward Island has its own vocabulary and dictionary.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] For example, angishore refers to a fisherman who is too lazy to fish and likely is a lexical item originating from Irish Gaelic settlers in Newfoundland.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Sarah Sawler, a writer from Halifax, highlights terms that are common to the Maritimes, such as dooryard for front yard, owly for when someone is angry or irritable, and biff for throw.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The term *college*, which refers to post-secondary education in general in the US, refers in Canada to either a post-secondary technical or vocational institution, or to one of the colleges that exist as federated schools within some Canadian universities.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Most often, a *college* is a community college, not a university.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In Canada, *college student* might denote someone obtaining a diploma in business management, graphic design, or nursing - an equivalent of this would be an associate degree in the United States (though "associate diplomas" may also be offered by some universities).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In contrast, *university student* is the term for someone earning a bachelor's degree, typically at a post-secondary university institution.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Hence, the term *going to college* in Canada does not have the same meaning as *going to university*, unless the speaker or context clarifies the specific level of post-secondary education that is meant.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Within the public school system the chief administrator of a school is generally "the principal", as in the United States, but the term is not used preceding their name, i.e., "Principal Smith".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The assistant to the principal is not titled as "assistant principal", but rather as "vice-principal", although the former is not unknown.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] This usage is identical to that in Northern Ireland.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In higher education, the head of an institution is "the president", though "principal" may also be used.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Many universities will often have a "chancellor", however this is principally a ceremonial role and typically does not confer administrative authority.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canadian universities publish *calendars* or *schedules*, not *catalogs* as in the US.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canadian students *write* or *take* exams (in the US, students generally "take" exams while teachers "write" them); they rarely *sit* them (standard British usage).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Those who supervise students during an exam are sometimes called *invigilators* as in Britain, or sometimes *proctors* as in the US; usage may depend on the region or even the individual institution.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Successive years of school are usually referred to as *grade one*, *grade two*, and so on.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In Quebec, Francophone speakers will often say *primary one*, *primary two* as a direct translation from the French, and so on; while Anglophones will say *grade one*, *grade two*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] These terms are comparable with the American *first grade, second grade* , English/Welsh *Year 1, Year 2*, Scottish/Northern Irish *Primary 1, Primary 2* or *P1, P2*, and Southern Irish *First Class, Second Class* and so on.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The year of school before grade 1 is usually called "Kindergarten", with the exception of Nova Scotia, where it is called "grade primary".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In addition, children younger than the public school start age may attend "pre-primary", although this is a newer addition to the Nova Scotian public-school system, and is not used frequently elsewhere.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In parts of the US, the four years of high school are termed the freshman, sophomore, junior, and senior years (terms also used for college years); in Canada, the specific levels are used instead, such as "grade nine" in lieu of freshman.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] As for higher education, only the term *freshman* (often reduced to *frosh*) has some currency in Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Moreover, some Canadian public-school systems have adolescents start high-school in "Grade 10" or, the sophomore year, although, this can depend on the province and even vary within a school-district.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The American usages "sophomore", "junior" and "senior" are not used in Canadian university terminology, or in speech.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The specific high-school grades and university years are therefore stated and individualized; for example, "Sarah is starting Grade 10 this year", which Americans would state as "Sarah is going to be a sophomore this year".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Similarly in the post-secondary education context, "Francois is in his second year of university" rather than the Americanism "Francois is a sophomore in college".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canadian students use the term *marks* (more common in England) or *grades* (more common in the US) to refer to their results.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Usage is mixed, although *marks* more commonly refer to a single score whereas *grades* often refers to the cumulative score in that class.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Unlike in the United States, use of metric units within a majority of industries is standard in Canada, as a result of the partial national adoption of the metric system during the mid-to-late 1970s that was eventually stalled; this has spawned some colloquial usages such as *klick* for kilometre.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Nonetheless, US units are still used in many situations.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Imperial volumes are also used, albeit rarely—although many Canadians and Americans mistakenly conflate the measurement systems despite their slight differences from each other (e.g.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] US, Canadian, and metric cups are 237 ml, 227 ml, and 250 mL respectively).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] For example, most English Canadians state their weight and height in pounds and feet/inches, respectively.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] This is also the case for many Quebec Francophones.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Distances while playing golf are always marked and discussed in yards, though official scorecards may also show metres.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Temperatures for cooking or pools are often given in Fahrenheit, while the weather is given in Celsius.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Directions in the Prairie provinces are sometimes given using miles, because the country roads generally follow the mile-based grid of the Dominion Land Survey.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Motor vehicle speed limits are measured in kilometres per hour.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canadians often measure distance in units of time when speaking, for example, saying a location is thirty minutes away when asked how far, rather than the actual distance.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canadians measure floor areas, both residential and commercial, in square feet or square metres.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Land area is in square feet, square metres, acres or hectares.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Fuel efficiency is more often discussed in the metric L/100 km than miles per US gallon.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The Letter paper size of 8.5 inches × 11 inches is used instead of the international and metric equivalent A4 size of 210 mm × 297 mm.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Beer cans are 355 mL (12 US oz), while beer bottles are typically 341 mL (12 Imperial oz), and draft beer is sold in various units; US or Imperial oz, US or Imperial pint, or occasionally mL.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Building materials are used in soft conversions of imperial sizes, but often purchased in relation to the imperial sizes.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] For example, 8-inch concrete masonry units can be referred to as an 8-inch CMU or 190 CMU.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The actual material used in the US and Canada is the same.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In Alberta, the generic *Trail* is often used to describe a freeway, expressway or major urban street (for example, Deerfoot Trail, Macleod Trail or Crowchild Trail in Calgary, Yellowhead Trail, Victoria Trail or Mark Messier/St.Albert Trail in Edmonton).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The British term *motorway* is not used.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The American terms *turnpike* and *tollway* for a toll road are not common.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The term *throughway* or *thruway* was used for first tolled limited-access highways (for example, the Deas Island Throughway, now Highway 99, from Vancouver, BC, to Blaine, Washington, US, or the Saint John Throughway (Highway 1) in Saint John, New Brunswick), but this term is not common anymore.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In everyday speech, when a particular roadway is not being specified, the term *highway* is generally or exclusively used.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The words *lawyer* and *counsel* (not *counsellor*) predominate in everyday contexts; the word *attorney* refers to any personal representative.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canadian lawyers generally do not refer to themselves as "attorneys", a term that is common in the United States.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The words *advocate* and *notary* – two distinct professions in Quebec civil law – are used to refer to that province's approximate equivalents of barrister and solicitor, respectively.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] It is not uncommon for English-speaking advocates in Quebec to refer to themselves in English as "barrister(s) and solicitor(s)", as most advocates chiefly perform what would traditionally be known as "solicitor's work", while only a minority of advocates actually appear in court.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In Canada's common law provinces and territories, the word *notary* means strictly a notary public.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Within the Canadian legal community itself, the word *solicitor* is often used to refer to any Canadian lawyer in general (much like the way the word *attorney* is used in the United States to refer to any American lawyer in general).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Despite the conceptual distinction between *barrister* and *solicitor*, Canadian court documents would contain a phrase such as "*John Smith,*solicitor*for the Plaintiff*" even though "John Smith" may well himself be the barrister who argues the case in court.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In a letter introducing him/herself to an opposing lawyer, a Canadian lawyer normally writes something like "*I am the*solicitor*for Mr.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The word *litigator* is also used by lawyers to refer to a fellow lawyer who specializes in lawsuits even though the more traditional word *barrister* is still employed to denote the same specialization.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Judges of Canada's superior courts, which exist at the provincial and territorial levels, are traditionally addressed as "My Lord" or "My Lady".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] This varies by jurisdiction, and some superior court judges prefer the titles "Mister Justice" or "Madam Justice" to "Lordship".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Judges of provincial or inferior courts are traditionally referred to in person as *"Your Honour"*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Judges of the Supreme Court of Canada and of the federal-level courts prefer the use of *"Mister/Madam (Chief) Justice"*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Justices of The Peace are addressed as *"Your Worship"*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] *"Your Honour"* is also the correct form of address for a Lieutenant Governor.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A serious crime is called an indictable offence, while a less-serious crime is called a summary conviction offence.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The older words felony and misdemeanour, which are still used in the United States, are not used in Canada's current *Criminal Code* (R.S.C.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] C-46) or by today's Canadian legal system.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] As noted throughout the *Criminal Code*, a person accused of a crime is called *the accused* and not *the defendant*, a term used instead in civil lawsuits.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In Canada, *visible minority* refers to a non-aboriginal person or group visibly not one of the majority race in a given population.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The term comes from the *Canadian Employment Equity Act*, which defines such people as "persons, other than Aboriginal people, who are non-Caucasian in race or non-white in colour." The term is used as a demographic category by Statistics Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The qualifier "visible" is used to distinguish such minorities from the "invisible" minorities determined by language (English vs.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] French) and certain distinctions in religion (Catholics vs.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A county in British Columbia means only a regional jurisdiction of the courts and justice system and is not otherwise connected to governance as with counties in other provinces and in the United States.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The rough equivalent to "county" as used elsewhere is a "Regional District".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The following are common in Canada, but not in the United States or the United Kingdom.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] One of the most distinctive Canadian phrases is the spoken interrogation or tag *eh*.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] This usage is also common in Queensland, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Other uses of *eh* – for instance, in place of *huh?* or *what?* meaning "please repeat or say again" – are also found in parts of the British Isles and Australia.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] It is common in Northern/Central Ontario, the Maritimes and the Prairie provinces.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The word *eh* is used quite frequently in the North Central dialect, so a Canadian accent is often perceived in people from North Dakota, Michigan, Minnesota, and Wisconsin.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A *rubber* in the US and Canada is slang for a condom.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In Canada, it sometimes means an eraser (as in the United Kingdom and Ireland).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The word *bum* can refer either to the buttocks (as in Britain), or to a homeless person (as in the US).
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Older Canadians may see "bum" as more polite than "butt", which before the 1980s was often considered rude.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The term *Canuck* simply means *Canadian* in its demonymic form, and, as a term used even by Canadians themselves, it is not considered derogatory.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The nickname Janey Canuck was used by Anglophone women's rights writer Emily Murphy in the 1920s and the *Johnny Canuck* comic book character of the 1940s.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Throughout the 1970s, Canada's winning World Cup men's downhill ski team was called the "Crazy Canucks" for their fearlessness on the slopes.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] It is also the name of the Vancouver Canucks, the National Hockey League team of Vancouver, British Columbia.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The term *hoser*, popularized by Bob & Doug McKenzie, typically refers to an uncouth, beer-swilling male and is a euphemism for "loser" coming from the earlier days of hockey played on an outdoor rink and the losing team would have to hose down the ice after the game so it froze smooth.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A *Newf* or *Newfie* is someone from Newfoundland and Labrador; sometimes considered derogatory.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] In Newfoundland, the term *Mainlander* refers to any Canadian (sometimes American, occasionally Labradorian) not from the island of Newfoundland.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] *Mainlander* is also occasionally used derogatorily.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A *Haligonian* refers to someone from the city of Halifax.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Cape Bretoners and Newfies (from Newfoundland and Labrador) often have similar slang.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] "Barmp" is often used as the sound a car horn makes, example: "He cut me off so I barmped the horn at him".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] When saying "B'y", while sounds like the traditional farewell, it is a syncopated shortening of the word "boy", referring to a person, example: "How's it goin, b'y?".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Another slang that is commonly used is "doohickey" which means an object, example: "Pass me that doohickey over there".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] When an individual uses the word "biffed", they mean that they threw something.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Example: "I got frustrated so I biffed it across the room".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Canadian English dialectology examines Canadian English through the use of written surveys due to the vastness of the country and the difficulties of conducting face-to-face interviews on a nationwide level.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] The historical overview of written surveys in Canadian-English dialectology includes Avis's study of speech differences among the Ontario-United States borders through the use of questionnaires.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] Another example is the Survey of Canadian English directed by Scargill.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p02] A more recent example would be Nylvek's survey of Saskatchewan English and Chambers' trans-Canada dialect questionnaires.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] An attitude study in the late 1970s revealed a positive attitude toward Canadian linguistic features.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Features include front vowel merger before /r/, low-back vowel merger, Canadian Raising, and Canadian lexical items.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Still, the sample group in British Columbia showed a preference for UK and US English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] This attitude sees a change years later.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] A survey about attitudes towards CE was conducted with a diverse sample group in Vancouver, BC, in 2009.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Among 429 Vancouverites, 81.1% believe there is a Canadian way of speaking English, 72.9% can tell CanE speakers from American English speakers, 69.1% consider CanE a part of their Canadian identity, and 74.1% think CanE should be taught in schools.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Due to the unavailability of free and easy-to-access CanE dictionaries, many Canadian opt for other non-Canadian English dictionaries today.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Historically, American, British, and Irish texts are used in Canadian schools for the most part; even though Canadian reference work was written and became available in the 1960s, they were never preferred as teaching material.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] A preference change can be seen at the end of higher education in Canada.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] At the University of Toronto's Graduate English department, "Canadian English" and a "consistent spelling" are officially "the standard for all Ph.D. dissertations," with the *Canadian Oxford English Dictionary* as the official guideline.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] However, there is no mention of which grammar guide was to be followed because there was never a solid standard developed for spelling and grammar.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] In 2011, just under 21.5 million Canadians, representing 65% of the population, spoke English most of the time at home, while 58% declared it their mother language.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] English is the major language everywhere in Canada except Quebec, and most Canadians (85%) can speak English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] While English is not the preferred language in Quebec, 36.1% of the Québécois can speak English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Nationally, Francophones are five times more likely to speak English than Anglophones are to speak French – 44% and 9% respectively.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Only 3.2% of Canada's English-speaking population resides in Quebec—mostly in Montreal.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] A study conducted in 2002 inquired Canadians from Ontario and Alberta about the "pleasantness" and "correctness" of different varieties of Canadian English based on province.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Albertans and Ontarians all seem to rate their English and BC English in the top three.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] However, both hold a low opinion of Quebec English.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Unlike the assumption that Toronto or Ontario English would be the most prestigious considering these regions are the most economically robust, BC had the best public opinion regarding pleasantness and correctness among the participants.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Jaan Lilles argues in an essay for *English Today* that there is no variety of "Canadian English." According to Lilles, Canadian English is simply not a "useful fiction".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] He goes on to argue that too often supposedly unique features of Canadian speakers, such as certain lexical terms such as *muskeg* are artificially exaggerated to distinguish Canadian speech primarily from that found in the United States.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] Lilles was heavily critiqued in the next issue of *English Today* by lexicographer Fraser Sutherland and others.
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] According to Stefan Dollinger, Lilles' paper "is not a paper based on any data or other new information but more of a pamphlet – so much so that it should not have been published without a public critique".
[src:tonne/canadian-english-p03] He continues, "The paper is insightful for different reasons: it is a powerful testimony of personal anecdote and opinion....
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum is a fossil fuel formed over millions of years from anaerobic decay of organic materials from buried prehistoric organisms, particularly plankton and algae.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] It is estimated that 70% of the world's oil deposits were formed during the Mesozoic, 20% were formed in the Cenozoic, and only 10% were formed in the Paleozoic.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Conventional reserves of petroleum are primarily recovered by drilling, which is performed after studying the relevant structural geology, analysis of the sedimentary basin, and characterization of the petroleum reservoir.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] There are also unconventional reserves such as oil sands and oil shale which are recovered using methods such as fracking.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Once extracted, oil is refined and separated, most easily by distillation, into numerous products for direct use or use in manufacturing.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum products include fuels such as gasoline (petrol), diesel, kerosene and jet fuel; bitumen, paraffin wax and lubricants; reagents used to make plastics; solvents, textiles, refrigerants, paint, synthetic rubber, fertilizers, pesticides, pharmaceuticals, and thousands of other petrochemicals.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum is used to manufacture a wide variety of materials essential for modern life, and it is estimated that the world consumes about 100 million barrels (16 million cubic metres) each day.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum production played a key role in industrialization and economic development, especially after the Second Industrial Revolution.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Some petroleum-rich countries, known as petrostates, gained significant economic and international influence during the latter half of the 20th century due to their control of oil production and trade.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum is a non-renewable natural resource, and its exploitation is damaging to the natural environment, climate system and human health.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Extraction, refining and burning of petroleum fuels counteract carbon sinks by releasing large quantities of greenhouse gases back into the Earth's atmosphere, making petroleum one of the major contributors to anthropogenic climate change.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Other negative environmental effects, at almost all stages of use, include direct release—such as oil spills—and secondary pollution of air and water sources.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Proximity to petroleum deposits, and subsequent access to and pricing of oil have historically fueled both domestic and geopolitical conflicts, state-sanctioned oil wars, diplomatic and trade frictions, energy policy disputes and other resource conflicts.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] While production is estimated to reach peak oil before 2035, global economic focus on climate change mitigation in the transition to renewable energy sources and increased electrification will greatly reduce dependency on petroleum.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The word *petroleum* comes from Medieval Latin *petroleum* (literally 'rock oil'), which comes from Latin *petra* 'rock' (from Greek *pétra* πέτρα) and *oleum* 'oil' (from Greek *élaion* ἔλαιον).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The origin of the term stems from monasteries in southern Italy where it was in use by the end of the first millennium as an alternative for the oldest term "naphtha".
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] After that, the term was used in numerous manuscripts and books, such as in the treatise *De Natura Fossilium*, published in 1546 by German mineralogist Georg Bauer.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] After the advent of the oil industry during the second half of the 19th century, the term became commonly known for the liquid form of hydrocarbons.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum in some form has been used since ancient times.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] More than 4,300 years ago, bitumen was mentioned when the Sumerians used it to make boats.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] A tablet of the legend of the birth of Sargon of Akkad mentions a basket which was closed by straw and bitumen.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] More than 4,000 years ago, according to Herodotus and Diodorus Siculus, asphalt (bitumen) was used in the construction of the walls and towers of Babylon; there were oil pits near Ardericca and Babylon and a pitch spring on Zakynthos.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In Babylon, petroleum was used for road construction, ship caulking, and medicine.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The use of petroleum in ancient China dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The *I Ching*, one of the earliest Chinese writings, cites that oil in its raw state, without refining, was first discovered, extracted, and used in China in the 1st century BCE.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In addition, the Chinese were the first to record the use of petroleum as fuel as early as the 4th century BCE.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] By 347 CE, oil was produced from bamboo-drilled wells in China.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the 7th century, petroleum was among the essential ingredients for Greek fire, an incendiary projectile weapon that was used by Byzantine Greeks against Arab ships attacking Constantinople.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Crude oil was distilled by Persian chemists, with clear descriptions given in Arabic handbooks such as those of Abu Bakr al-Razi.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the 9th century, oil fields were exploited in the area around modern Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] These fields were described by Abu Bakr al-Razi in the 10th century and by Marco Polo in the 13th century, who describes the output of those wells as hundreds of shiploads.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Arab and Persian chemists distilled crude oil to produce flammable products for military purposes.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Through Islamic Spain, distillation became available in Western Europe by the 12th century.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] It was present in Romania since the 13th century, being recorded as păcură.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Sophisticated oil pits, 4.5 to 6 metres (15 to 20 ft) deep, were dug by the Seneca people and other Iroquois in Western Pennsylvania as early as 1415–1450.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The French General Louis-Joseph de Montcalm encountered Seneca using petroleum for ceremonial fires and as a healing lotion during a visit to Fort Duquesne in 1750.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Early British explorers to Myanmar documented a flourishing oil extraction industry based in Yenangyaung that, in 1795, had hundreds of hand-dug wells under production.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Merkwiller-Pechelbronn is said to be the first European site where petroleum has been explored and used.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The still active Erdpechquelle, a spring where petroleum appears mixed with water, has been used since 1498, notably for medical purposes.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the mid-19th century, oil wells developed quickly in various parts of the world, though the title of the "first oil well" depends on the criteria.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In 1846, a group of Russian Imperial engineers directed by Major Alexeyev of the Bakinskii Corps of Mining Engineers accidentally struck oil while hand-drilling with a primitive percussion rig in Bibi-Heybat, near Baku (now Azerbaijan), though they were not specifically searching for oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In 1853, Ignacy Łukasiewicz, who discovered how to distill kerosene from seep crude oil and invented the modern kerosene lamp, hand-dug the first intentional well for commercial oil extraction in Bóbrka, Poland, to supply fuel for lighting (still operational as of 2025).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] A hand-dug well and another refinery followed in 1857 near Ploiești, Romania.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Romania (then a vassal of the Ottoman Empire) was the first country in the world to have its annual crude oil output officially recorded in international statistics – 275 tonnes for 1857.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In 1858, Georg Christian Konrad Hunäus found a significant amount of petroleum while drilling for lignite in Wietze, Germany.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Wietze later provided about 80% of German consumption in the Wilhelmine Era.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The production stopped in 1963, but Wietze has hosted a petroleum museum since 1970.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Oil sands have been mined since the 18th century.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In Wietze, natural asphalt/bitumen has been explored since the 18th century.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Both in Pechelbronn as in Wietze, the coal industry dominated the petroleum technologies.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Chemist James Young in 1847 noticed a natural petroleum seepage in the coal mine at Riddings, Derbyshire, from which he distilled a light thin oil suitable for use as lamp oil, at the same time obtaining a more viscous oil suitable for lubricating machinery.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In 1848, Young set up a small business refining crude oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Young eventually succeeded (by distilling cannel coal at low heat) in creating a fluid resembling petroleum, which when treated in the same way as the seep oil gave similar products.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Young found that by slow distillation he could obtain several useful liquids from it, one of which he named "paraffine oil" because at low temperatures it congealed into a substance resembling paraffin wax.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The production of these oils and solid paraffin wax from coal formed the subject of his patent dated October 17, 1850.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In 1850, Young & Meldrum and Edward William Binney entered into partnership under the title of E.W.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Binney & Co. at Bathgate in West Lothian and E.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Meldrum & Co. at Glasgow; their works at Bathgate were completed in 1851 and became the first truly commercial oil-works in the world with the first modern oil refinery.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The demand for petroleum as a fuel for lighting in North America and around the world quickly grew.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The first oil well in the Americas was drilled in 1859 by Edwin Drake at what is now called the Drake Well in Cherrytree Township, Pennsylvania.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] There also was a company associated with it, and it sparked an oil boom and rapid expansion of the global petroleum industry.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The same year, engine-drilled wells appeared in West Virginia.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The first commercial oil well in Canada became operational in 1858 at Oil Springs, Ontario.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Businessman James Miller Williams dug several wells between 1855 and 1858 before discovering a rich reserve of oil four metres below ground.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Williams extracted 1.5 million litres of crude oil by 1860, refining much of it into kerosene lamp oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Williams's well became commercially viable a year before Drake's Pennsylvania operation and could be argued to be the first commercial oil well in North America.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The discovery at Oil Springs touched off an oil boom which brought hundreds of speculators and workers to the area.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Advances in drilling continued into 1862 when local driller Shaw reached a depth of 62 metres using the spring-pole drilling method.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] On January 16, 1862, after an explosion of natural gas, Canada's first oil gusher came into production, shooting into the air at a recorded rate of 480 cubic metres (3,000 bbl) per day.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] By the end of the 19th century the Russian Empire, particularly the Branobel company in Azerbaijan, had taken the lead in production.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the 1930s, Alfred Treibs determined the biological origin of petroleum, which was previously controversial.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Access to oil was a major factor in several military conflicts of the 20th century, including World War II, during which oil facilities were a major strategic asset and were extensively bombed.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The German invasion of the Soviet Union included the goal to capture the Baku oilfields, as it would provide much-needed oil supplies for the German military which was suffering from blockades.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Oil exploration in North America during the early 20th century led to the U.S. becoming the leading producer by mid-century.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] As petroleum production in the U.S. peaked during the 1960s, the United States was surpassed by Saudi Arabia and the Soviet Union in total output.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] During the 1973 oil crisis, Saudi Arabia and other Arab nations imposed an oil embargo against the United States, the United Kingdom, Japan and other Western nations which supported Israel in the Yom Kippur War.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] This was followed by the 1979 oil crisis, which was caused by a drop in oil production in the wake of the Iranian Revolution and caused oil prices to more than double.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The two oil price shocks had many short and long-term effects on global politics and the global economy.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] They led to sustained reductions in demand as a result of substitution to other fuels, especially coal and nuclear, and improvements in energy efficiency, facilitated by government policies.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] High oil prices also induced investment in oil production by non-OPEC countries, including Prudhoe Bay in Alaska, the North Sea offshore fields of the United Kingdom and Norway, the Cantarell offshore field of Mexico, and oil sands in Canada.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] About 90 percent of vehicular fuel needs are met by oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum makes up 40 percent of total energy consumption in the United States, but is responsible for only one percent of electricity generation.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum's worth as a portable, dense energy source powering the vast majority of vehicles and as the base of many industrial chemicals makes it one of the world's most important commodities.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The top three oil-producing countries as of 2018 are the United States, Russia, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In 2018, due in part to developments in hydraulic fracturing and horizontal drilling, the United States became the world's largest producer.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] About 80 percent of the world's readily accessible reserves are located in the Middle East, with 62.5 percent coming from the Arab five: Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates, Iraq, Qatar, and Kuwait.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] A large portion of the world's total oil exists as unconventional sources, such as bitumen in Athabasca oil sands and extra heavy oil in the Orinoco Belt.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] While significant volumes of oil are extracted from oil sands, particularly in Canada, logistical and technical hurdles remain, as oil extraction requires large amounts of heat and water, making its net energy content quite low relative to conventional crude oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Thus, Canada's oil sands are not expected to provide more than a few million barrels per day in the foreseeable future.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Many modern geopolitical conflicts are to do with petroleum.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum consists of a variety of liquid, gaseous, and solid components.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Lighter hydrocarbons are the gases methane, ethane, propane and butane.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Otherwise the bulk of the liquid and solids are largely heavier organic compounds, often hydrocarbons (C and H only).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The proportion of light hydrocarbons in a petroleum mixture varies among oil fields.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] An oil well produces predominantly crude oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Because the pressure is lower at the surface than underground, some of the gas will come out of solution and be recovered (or burned) as *associated gas* or *solution gas*.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] A gas well produces predominantly natural gas.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The hydrocarbons in crude oil are mostly alkanes, cycloalkanes and various aromatic hydrocarbons, while the other organic compounds contain nitrogen, oxygen, and sulfur, and traces of metals such as iron, nickel, copper and vanadium.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Many oil reservoirs contain live bacteria.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Four different types of hydrocarbon appear in crude oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The relative percentage of each varies, determining the properties of each oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The alkanes from pentane (C5H12) to octane (C8H18) are refined into gasoline, the ones from nonane (C9H20) to hexadecane (C16H34) into diesel fuel, kerosene and jet fuel.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Alkanes with more than 16 carbon atoms can be refined into fuel oil and lubricating oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] At the heavier end of the range, paraffin wax is an alkane with approximately 25 carbon atoms, while asphalt has 35 and up, although these are usually cracked in modern refineries into more valuable products.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The lightest fraction, the so-called petroleum gases, are subjected to diverse processing depending on cost.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] These gases are either flared off, sold as liquefied petroleum gas, or used to power the refinery's own burners.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] During the winter, butane (C4H10) is blended into the gasoline pool at high rates because its high vapour pressure assists with cold starts.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The *aromatic hydrocarbons* are unsaturated hydrocarbons that have one or more benzene rings.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] They tend to burn with a sooty flame, and many have a sweet aroma.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] These different components are separated by fractional distillation at an oil refinery to produce gasoline, jet fuel, kerosene, and other hydrocarbon fractions.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The components in an oil sample can be determined by gas chromatography and mass spectrometry.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Due to the large number of co-eluted hydrocarbons within oil, many cannot be resolved by traditional gas chromatography.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] This unresolved complex mixture (UCM) of hydrocarbons is particularly apparent when analysing weathered oils and extracts from tissues of organisms exposed to oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Crude oil varies greatly in appearance depending on its composition.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] It is usually black or dark brown (although it may be yellowish, reddish, or even greenish).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the reservoir it is usually found in association with natural gas (which being lighter forms a "gas cap" over the petroleum) and saline water (which being heavier than most forms of crude oil, generally sinks beneath it).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Crude oil may also be found in a semi-solid form mixed with sand and water, as in the Athabasca oil sands in Canada, where it is usually referred to as crude bitumen.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In Canada, bitumen is considered a sticky, black, tar-like form of crude oil which is so thick and heavy that it must be heated or diluted before it will flow.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Venezuela also has large amounts of oil in the Orinoco oil sands, although the hydrocarbons trapped in them are less viscous than in Canada and are usually called extra heavy oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Oil sands resources are called unconventional oil to distinguish them from oil which can be extracted using traditional oil well methods.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Between them, Canada and Venezuela contain an estimated 3.6 trillion barrels (570×10^9 m3) of bitumen and extra heavy oil, about twice the volume of the world's reserves of conventional oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum is a fossil fuel derived from fossilized organic materials, such as zooplankton and algae.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Vast amounts of these remains settled to sea or lake bottoms where they were covered in stagnant water (water with no dissolved oxygen) or sediments (such as mud and silt) faster than they could decompose aerobically.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Approximately 1 m below this sediment, water oxygen concentration was low, below 0.1 mg/L, and anoxic conditions existed.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] As further layers settled into the sea or lake bed, intense heat and pressure built up in the lower regions.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] This process caused the organic matter to change, first into a waxy material known as kerogen (found in various oil shales around the world) and then with more heat into liquid and gaseous hydrocarbons via a process known as catagenesis.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Formation of petroleum occurs from hydrocarbon pyrolysis in a variety of mainly endothermic reactions at high temperatures or pressures, or both.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] These phases are described in detail below.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the absence of plentiful oxygen, *aerobic* bacteria were prevented from decaying the organic matter after it was buried under a layer of sediment or water.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] However, *anaerobic* bacteria were able to reduce sulfates and nitrates among the matter to H2S and N2 respectively by using the matter as a source for other reactants.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Due to such anaerobic bacteria, at first, this matter began to break apart mostly via hydrolysis: polysaccharides and proteins were hydrolyzed to simple sugars and amino acids respectively.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] These were further anaerobically oxidized at an accelerated rate by the enzymes of the bacteria: e.g., proteins went through oxidative deamination to amino acids, which in turn reacted further to ammonia and α-keto acids.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Monosaccharides in turn ultimately decayed to CO2 and methane.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The anaerobic decay products of amino acids, monosaccharides, phenols and aldehydes combined into fulvic acids.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Fats and waxes were not extensively hydrolyzed under these mild conditions.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Some phenolic compounds produced from previous reactions worked as bactericides and the Actinomycetales order of bacteria also produced antibiotic compounds (e.g., streptomycin).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Thus the action of anaerobic bacteria ceased at about 10 m below the water or sediment.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The mixture at this depth contained fulvic acids, unreacted and partially reacted fats and waxes, slightly modified lignin, resins and other hydrocarbons.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] As more layers of organic matter settled into the sea or lake bed, intense heat and pressure built up in the lower regions.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] As a consequence, compounds of this mixture began to combine in poorly understood ways to kerogen.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Combination happened in a similar fashion as phenol and formaldehyde molecules react to urea-formaldehyde resins, but kerogen formation occurred in a more complex manner due to a bigger variety of reactants.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The total process of kerogen formation from the beginning of anaerobic decay is called **diagenesis**, a word that means a transformation of materials by dissolution and recombination of their constituents.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Kerogen formation continued to a depth of about 1 km from the Earth's surface where temperatures may reach around 50 °C.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Kerogen formation represents a halfway point between organic matter and fossil fuels: kerogen can be exposed to oxygen, oxidize and thus be lost, or it could be buried deeper inside the Earth's crust and be subjected to conditions which allow it to slowly transform into fossil fuels like petroleum.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The latter happened through **catagenesis** in which the reactions were mostly radical rearrangements of kerogen.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] These reactions took thousands to millions of years, and no external reactants were involved.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Due to the radical nature of these reactions, kerogen reacted towards two classes of products: those with low H/C ratio (anthracene or products similar to it) and those with high H/C ratio (methane or products similar to it); i.e., carbon-rich or hydrogen-rich products.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Because catagenesis was closed off from external reactants, the resulting composition of the fuel mixture was dependent on the composition of the kerogen via reaction stoichiometry.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Three types of kerogen exist: type I (algal), II (liptinic) and III (humic), which were formed mainly from algae, plankton and woody plants (this term includes trees, shrubs and lianas) respectively.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The hydrocarbon-generating potential and thermal maturity of petroleum source rocks are commonly evaluated using Rock-Eval pyrolysis and vitrinite reflectance measurements, which provide quantitative indicators of organic matter type, maturation level, and the likelihood of oil or gas generation.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Catagenesis was pyrolytic despite the fact that it happened at relatively low temperatures (when compared to commercial pyrolysis plants) of 60 to several hundred °C.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Pyrolysis was possible because of the long reaction times involved.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Heat for catagenesis came from the decomposition of radioactive materials of the crust, especially 40K, 232Th, 235U and 238U.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The heat varied with geothermal gradient and was typically 10–30 °C per km of depth from the Earth's surface.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Unusual magma intrusions, however, could have created greater localized heating.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Geologists often refer to the temperature range in which oil forms as an *"oil window"*.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Below the minimum temperature oil remains trapped in the form of kerogen.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Above the maximum temperature the oil is converted to natural gas through the process of thermal cracking.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Sometimes, oil formed at extreme depths may migrate and become trapped at a much shallower level.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The Athabasca oil sands are one example of this.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] An alternative mechanism to the one described above was proposed by Russian scientists in the mid-1850s, the hypothesis of abiogenic petroleum origin (petroleum formed by inorganic means), but this is contradicted by geological and geochemical evidence.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Abiogenic sources of oil have been found but never in commercially profitable amounts.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] "The controversy isn't over whether abiogenic oil reserves exist," said Larry Nation of the American Association of Petroleum Geologists.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Within these reservoirs, fluids will typically organize themselves like a three-layer cake with a layer of water below the oil layer and a layer of gas above it, although the different layers vary in size between reservoirs.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Because most hydrocarbons are less dense than rock or water, they often migrate upward through adjacent rock layers until either reaching the surface or becoming trapped within porous rocks (known as reservoirs) by impermeable rocks above.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] However, the process is influenced by underground water flows, causing oil to migrate hundreds of kilometres horizontally or even short distances downward before becoming trapped in a reservoir.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] When hydrocarbons are concentrated in a trap, an oil field forms, from which the liquid can be extracted by drilling and pumping.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The reactions that produce oil and natural gas are often modeled as first order breakdown reactions, where hydrocarbons are broken down to oil and natural gas by a set of parallel reactions, and oil eventually breaks down to natural gas by another set of reactions.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The latter set is regularly used in petrochemical plants and oil refineries.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum has mostly been recovered by oil drilling (natural petroleum springs are rare).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Drilling is carried out after studies of structural geology (at the reservoir scale), sedimentary basin analysis, and reservoir characterisation (mainly in terms of the porosity and permeability of geologic reservoir structures).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Wells are drilled into oil reservoirs to extract the crude oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] "Natural lift" production methods that rely on the natural reservoir pressure to force the oil to the surface are usually sufficient for a while after reservoirs are first tapped.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In some reservoirs, such as in the Middle East, the natural pressure is sufficient over a long time.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The natural pressure in most reservoirs, however, eventually dissipates.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Then the oil must be extracted using "artificial lift" means.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Over time, these "primary" methods become less effective and "secondary" production methods may be used.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] A common secondary method is "waterflood" or injection of water into the reservoir to increase pressure and force the oil to the drilled shaft or "wellbore".
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Eventually "tertiary" or "enhanced" oil recovery methods may be used to increase the oil's flow characteristics by injecting steam, carbon dioxide and other gases or chemicals into the reservoir.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the United States, primary production methods account for less than 40 percent of the oil produced on a daily basis, secondary methods account for about 50 percent, and tertiary recovery the remaining 10 percent.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Extracting oil (or "bitumen") from oil/tar sand and oil shale deposits requires mining the sand or shale and heating it in a vessel or retort, or using "in-situ" methods of injecting heated liquids into the deposit and then pumping the liquid back out saturated with oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Oil-eating bacteria biodegrade oil that has escaped to the surface.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Oil sands are reservoirs of partially biodegraded oil still in the process of escaping and being biodegraded, but they contain so much migrating oil that, although most of it has escaped, vast amounts are still present—more than can be found in conventional oil reservoirs.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The lighter fractions of the crude oil are destroyed first, resulting in reservoirs containing an extremely heavy form of crude oil, called crude bitumen in Canada, or extra-heavy crude oil in Venezuela.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] These two countries have the world's largest deposits of oil sands.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] On the other hand, oil shales are source rocks that have not been exposed to heat or pressure long enough to convert their trapped hydrocarbons into crude oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Technically speaking, oil shales are not always shales and do not contain oil, but are fined-grain sedimentary rocks containing an insoluble organic solid called kerogen.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The kerogen in the rock can be converted into crude oil using heat and pressure to simulate natural processes.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The method has been known for centuries and was patented in 1694 under British Crown Patent No.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] 330 covering, "A way to extract and make great quantities of pitch, tar, and oil out of a sort of stone." Although oil shales are found in many countries, the United States has the world's largest deposits.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The petroleum industry generally classifies crude oil by the geographic location it is produced in (e.g., West Texas Intermediate, Brent, or Oman), its API gravity (an oil industry measure of density), and its sulfur content.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Crude oil may be considered *light* if it has low density, *heavy* if it has high density, or *medium* if it has a density between that of *light* and *heavy*.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Additionally, it may be referred to as *sweet* if it contains relatively little sulfur or *sour* if it contains substantial amounts of sulfur.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The geographic location is important because it affects transportation costs to the refinery.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] *Light* crude oil is more desirable than *heavy* oil since it produces a higher yield of gasoline, while *sweet* oil commands a higher price than *sour* oil because it has fewer environmental problems and requires less refining to meet sulfur standards imposed on fuels in consuming countries.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Each crude oil has unique molecular characteristics which are revealed by the use of crude oil assay analysis in petroleum laboratories.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Barrels from an area in which the crude oil's molecular characteristics have been determined and the oil has been classified are used as pricing references throughout the world.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] There are declining amounts of these benchmark oils being produced each year, so other oils are more commonly what is actually delivered.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In terms of volume, most petroleum is converted into fuels for combustion engines.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In terms of value, petroleum underpins the petrochemical industry, which includes many high value products such as pharmaceuticals and plastics.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] By volume, 84% of hydrocarbons present in petroleum are converted into fuels.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Due to its high energy density, easy transportability and relative abundance, oil has become the world's most important source of energy since the mid-1950s.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum is used mostly, by volume, for refining into fuel oil and gasoline, both important *primary energy* sources. , including gasoline, diesel, jet, heating, and other fuel oils, and liquefied petroleum gas.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Closely related to fuels for combustion engines are Lubricants, greases, and viscosity stabilizers.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Many pharmaceuticals are derived from petroleum, albeit via multi-step processes.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Modern medicine depends on petroleum as a source of building blocks, reagents, and solvents.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Similarly, virtually all pesticides, insecticides, and herbicides are derived from petroleum.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Pesticides have profoundly affected life expectancies by controlling disease vectors and by increasing crop yield.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Like pharmaceuticals, pesticides are in essence petrochemicals.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Almost all plastics and synthetic polymers are derived from petroleum, which is the source of monomers.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Alkenes (olefins) are one important class of these precursor molecules.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The petroleum industry, also known as the oil industry, includes the global processes of exploration, extraction, refining, transportation (often by oil tankers and pipelines), and marketing of petroleum products.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The largest volume products of the industry are fuel oil and gasoline (petrol).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum is also the raw material for many chemical products, including pharmaceuticals, solvents, fertilizers, pesticides, synthetic fragrances, and plastics.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The industry is usually divided into three major components: upstream, midstream, and downstream.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Upstream regards exploration and extraction of crude oil, midstream encompasses transportation and storage of it, and downstream concerns refining crude oil into various end products.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum is vital to many industries, and is necessary for the maintenance of industrial civilization in its current configuration, making it a critical concern for many nations.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Oil accounts for a large percentage of the world's energy consumption, ranging from a low of 32% for Europe and Asia, to a high of 53% for the Middle East.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Other geographic regions' consumption patterns are as follows: South and Central America (44%), Africa (41%), and North America (40%).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The world consumes 36 billion barrels (5.8 km3) of oil per year, with developed nations being the largest consumers.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The United States consumed 18% of the oil produced in 2015.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The production, distribution, refining, and retailing of petroleum taken as a whole represents the world's largest industry in terms of dollar value.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum transport is the transportation of petroleum and derivatives such as gasoline (petrol).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum products are transported via rail cars, trucks, tanker vessels, and pipeline networks.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The method used to move the petroleum products depends on the volume that is being moved and its destination.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Land-based transportation modes such as pipelines and rail each have strengths and weaknesses.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] One of the key differences is the cost associated with transporting petroleum though pipeline or rail.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The risks with moving petroleum products are pollution related and the chance of spillage.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Petroleum oil is very hard to clean up and is very toxic to living animals and their surroundings.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the 1950s, shipping costs made up 33% of the price of oil transported from the Persian Gulf to the United States, but with the development of supertankers in the 1970s, the cost of shipping dropped to 5% of the price of Persian oil in the US.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] The share of the shipping cost on the final cost of the delivered commodity was less than 3% in 2010.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Oil prices are determined by global supply and demand, rather than any country's domestic production level, although the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) cartel increases oil prices.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Crude oil is traded as a future on both the NYMEX and ICE exchanges.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Futures contracts are agreements in which buyers and sellers agree to purchase and deliver specific amounts of physical crude oil on a given date in the future.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] A contract covers any multiple of 1,000 barrels and can be purchased up to nine years into the future.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In the 2021 US Energy Information Administration (EIA) estimate, the world consumes 97.26 million barrels of oil each day.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Top oil-producing countries from 1973 to 2018.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] In petroleum industry parlance, *production* refers to the quantity of crude extracted from reserves, not the literal creation of the product.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] 2 Canadian statistics are complicated by the fact it is both an importer and exporter of crude oil, and refines large amounts of oil for the U.S. market.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] It is the leading source of U.S. imports of oil and products, averaging 2,500,000 bbl/d (400,000 m3/d) in August 2007.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Total world production/consumption (as of 2005) is approximately 84 million barrels per day (13,400,000 m3/d).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p01] Countries whose oil production is 10% or less of their consumption.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] As of 2018, about a quarter of annual global greenhouse gas emissions is the carbon dioxide from burning petroleum (plus methane leaks from the industry).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Along with the burning of coal, petroleum combustion is the largest contributor to the increase in atmospheric CO2.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Atmospheric CO2 has risen over the last 150 years to current levels of over 415 ppmv, from the 180–300 ppmv of the prior 800 thousand years.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The rise in Arctic temperature has reduced the minimum Arctic ice pack to 4,320,000 km2 (1,670,000 sq mi), a loss of almost half since satellite measurements started in 1979.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Ocean acidification is the increase in the acidity of the Earth's oceans caused by the uptake of CO2 from the atmosphere.The saturation state of calcium carbonate decreases with the uptake of carbon dioxide in the ocean.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] This increase in acidity inhibits all marine life—having a greater effect on smaller organisms as well as shelled organisms such as Pectinoidea.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Oil extraction is simply the removal of oil from the reservoir (oil pool).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] There are many methods of extracting the oil from the reservoirs for example; mechanical shaking, water-in-oil emulsion, and specialty chemicals called demulsifiers that separate the oil from water.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Oil extraction is costly and often environmentally damaging.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Offshore exploration and extraction of oil disturb the surrounding marine environment.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Crude oil and refined fuel spills from tanker ship accidents have damaged natural ecosystems and human livelihoods in Alaska, the Gulf of Mexico, the Galápagos Islands, France and many other places.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The quantity of oil spilled during accidents has ranged from a few hundred tons to several hundred thousand tons (e.g., Deepwater Horizon oil spill, SS Atlantic Empress, Amoco Cadiz).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Smaller spills have already proven to have a great impact on ecosystems, such as the *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Oil spills at sea are generally much more damaging than those on land, since they can spread for hundreds of square miles in a thin oil slick which can cover beaches with a thin coating of oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] This can kill sea birds, mammals, shellfish, and other organisms it coats.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Oil spills on land are more readily containable if a makeshift earth dam can be rapidly bulldozed around the spill site before most of the oil escapes, and land animals can avoid the oil more easily.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Control of oil spills is difficult, requiring ad hoc methods and often a large amount of manpower.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The dropping of bombs and incendiary devices from aircraft on the SS *Torrey Canyon* wreck produced poor results; modern techniques would include pumping the oil from the wreck, like in the *Prestige* oil spill or the *Erika* oil spill.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] These compounds have a very high water solubility and thus tend to dissolve and move with water.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Certain naturally occurring bacteria such as *Micrococcus*, *Arthrobacter*, and *Rhodococcus* have been shown to degrade these contaminants.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Because petroleum is a naturally occurring substance, its presence in the environment is not necessarily the result of human causes such as accidents and routine activities (seismic exploration, drilling, extraction, refining and combustion).
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Phenomena such as seeps and tar pits are examples of areas that petroleum affects without human involvement.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] A tarball is a blob of crude oil (not to be confused with tar, which is a human-made product derived from pine trees or refined from petroleum) which has been weathered after floating in the ocean.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Tarballs are an aquatic pollutant in most environments, although they can occur naturally, for example in the Santa Barbara Channel of California or in the Gulf of Mexico off Texas.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Their concentration and features have been used to assess the extent of oil spills.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Their composition can be used to identify their sources of origin, and tarballs may be dispersed over long distances by deep sea currents.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] They are slowly decomposed by bacteria, including *Chromobacterium violaceum*, *Cladosporium resinae*, *Bacillus submarinus*, *Micrococcus varians*, *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Candida marina* and *Saccharomyces estuari*.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] In 2018 road transport used 49% of petroleum, aviation 8%, and uses other than energy 17%.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Electric vehicles are the main alternative for road transport and biojet for aviation.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Single-use plastics have a high carbon footprint and may pollute the sea, but as of 2022 the best alternatives are unclear.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Control of petroleum production has been a significant driver of international relations during much of the 20th and 21st centuries.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Organizations like OPEC have played an outsized role in international politics.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Some historians and commentators have called this the "Age of Oil" With the rise of renewable energy and addressing climate change some commentators expect a realignment of international power away from petrostates.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] "Oil rents" have been described as connected with corruption in political literature.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] A 2011 study suggests that increases in oil rents increased corruption in countries with heavy government involvement in the production of oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The study found that increases in oil rents "significantly deteriorates political rights".
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The investigators say that oil exploitation gave politicians "an incentive to extend civil liberties but reduce political rights in the presence of oil windfalls to evade redistribution and conflict".
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Petroleum production has been linked with conflict for many years, leading to thousands of deaths.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Petroleum deposits are in very few countries around the world.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Conflicts may start when countries refuse to cut oil production in which other countries respond to such actions by increasing their production causing a trade war as experienced during the 2020 Russia–Saudi Arabia oil price war.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Other conflicts start with countries wanting petroleum resources or other reasons on oil resource territory experienced in the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC /ˈoʊpɛk/ *OH-pek*) is an intergovernmental cartel enabling the co-operation of leading oil-producing and oil-dependent countries in order to collectively influence the global oil market and maximize profit.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] It was founded on 14 September 1960 in Baghdad by the first five members: Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The organization, which currently comprises 11 member countries, accounted for 38 percent of global oil production in 2022.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] It is estimated that 79.5 percent of the world's proven oil reserves are located within OPEC nations, with the Middle East alone accounting for 67.2 percent of OPEC's total reserves.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] In a series of steps in the 1960s and 1970s, OPEC restructured the global system of oil production in favor of oil-producing states and away from an oligopoly of dominant Anglo-American oil firms, the "Seven Sisters".
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] In the 1970s, restrictions in oil production led to a dramatic rise in oil prices with long-lasting and far-reaching consequences for the global economy.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Since the 1980s, OPEC has had a limited impact on world oil-supply and oil-price stability, as there is frequent cheating by members on their commitments to one another, and as member commitments reflect what they would do even in the absence of OPEC.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The formation of OPEC marked a turning point toward national sovereignty over natural resources.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] OPEC decisions have come to play a prominent role in the global oil market and in international relations.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Economists have characterized OPEC as a textbook example of a cartel, a group whose members cooperate to reduce market competition and obtain monopoly profits.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The current OPEC members are Algeria, Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, the Republic of the Congo, Saudi Arabia, and Venezuela.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The former members are Angola, Ecuador, Indonesia, Qatar, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] OPEC+ is a larger group consisting of OPEC members and other oil-producing countries.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] It was formed in late 2016 to better control the global crude oil market.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Canada, Egypt, Norway, and Oman have attended some meetings as observers.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The United Arab Emirates left both OPEC and OPEC+ in 2026.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Consumption in the 20th and 21st centuries has been abundantly pushed by automobile sector growth.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The 1985–2003 oil glut even fueled the sales of low fuel economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The 2008 economic crisis seems to have had some impact on the sales of such vehicles; still, in 2008 oil consumption showed a small increase.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] In 2016 Goldman Sachs predicted lower demand for oil due to emerging economies concerns, especially China.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The BRICS (Brasil, Russia, India, China, South Africa) countries might also kick in, as China briefly had the largest automobile market in December 2009.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] A detailed review of International Energy Agency oil projections have revealed that revisions of world oil production, price and investments have been motivated by a combination of demand and supply factors.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] All together, non-OPEC conventional projections have been fairly stable the last 15 years, while downward revisions were mainly allocated to OPEC.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Upward revisions are primarily a result of US tight oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Production will also face an increasingly complex situation; while OPEC countries still have large reserves at low production prices, newly found reservoirs often lead to higher prices; offshore giants such as Tupi, Guara and Tiber demand high investments and ever-increasing technological abilities.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Subsalt reservoirs such as Tupi were unknown in the 20th century, mainly because the industry was unable to probe them.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Enhanced oil recovery techniques such as those used at the Daqing Oil Field will continue to play a major role in increasing the world's recoverable oil.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The expected availability of petroleum resources has always been around 35 years or even less since the start of the modern exploration.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The oil constant, an insider pun in the German industry, refers to that effect.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] A growing number of divestment campaigns from major funds pushed by newer generations who question the sustainability of petroleum may hinder the financing of future oil prospection and production.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The peak of oil discoveries was in 1965, and oil production per year has surpassed oil discoveries every year since 1980.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Lack of knowledge and/or transparency in the accounting of global oil reserves makes it difficult to predict the oil peak in any given region.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Based on available production data, proponents have previously predicted the peak for the world in 1989, 1995, or 1995–2000.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Some of these predictions date from before the recession of the early 1980s and the consequent lowering in global consumption, the effect of which was to delay the date of any peak by several years.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Just as the 1971 U.S. peak in oil production was only clearly recognized after the fact, a peak in world production will be difficult to discern until production clearly drops off.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] In 2020, according to BP's Energy Outlook 2020, peak oil had been reached, due to the changing energy landscape coupled with the economic toll of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] While there has been much focus historically on peak oil supply, the focus is increasingly shifting to peak demand as more countries seek to transition to renewable energy.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The GeGaLo index of geopolitical gains and losses assesses how the geopolitical position of 156 countries may change if the world fully transitions to renewable energy resources.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Former oil exporters are expected to lose power, while the positions of former oil importers and countries rich in renewable energy resources is expected to strengthen.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] The calculus for peak oil has changed with the introduction of unconventional production methods.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] In particular, the combination of horizontal drilling and hydraulic fracturing has resulted in a significant increase in production from previously uneconomic plays.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Certain rock strata contain hydrocarbons but have low permeability and are not thick from a vertical perspective.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Conventional vertical wells would be unable to economically retrieve these hydrocarbons.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Horizontal drilling, extending horizontally through the strata, permits the well to access a much greater volume of the strata.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Hydraulic fracturing creates greater permeability and increases hydrocarbon flow to the wellbore.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] On Saturn's largest moon, Titan, lakes of liquid hydrocarbons comprising methane, ethane, propane and other constituents occur naturally.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Data collected by the space probe *Cassini–Huygens* yield an estimate that the visible lakes and seas of Titan contain about 300 times the volume of Earth's proven oil reserves.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Drilled samples from the surface of Mars taken in 2015 by the *Curiosity* rover's Mars Science Laboratory have found organic molecules of benzene and propane in 3-billion-year-old rock samples in Gale Crater.
[src:tonne/crude-oil-p02] Petrofiction or oil fiction is a genre of fiction focused on the role of petroleum in society.
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] The **cubic metre** (in Commonwealth English and international spelling as used by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures) or **cubic meter** (in American English) is the unit of volume in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] It is the volume of a cube with edges one metre in length.
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] An alternative name, which allowed a different usage with metric prefixes, was the stère, still sometimes used for dry measure (for instance, in reference to wood).
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] Another alternative name, no longer widely used, was the **kilolitre**.
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] The acronym **CBM** is in common use to describe a cubic metre.
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] A cubic metre of pure water at the temperature of maximum density (3.983 °C) and standard atmospheric pressure (101.325 kPa) has a mass of 1000 kg, or one tonne, which makes its maximum density at 101.325 kPa 1 Mg/m3.
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] At 0 °C, the freezing point of water, a cubic metre of water has slightly less mass, 999.85 kilograms.
[src:tonne/cubic-metre] The "cubic metre" symbol is encoded by Unicode at code point U+33A5 ㎥ SQUARE M CUBED.
[src:tonne/drum-container] A **drum** (also called a barrel) is a cylindrical shipping container used for shipping bulk cargo.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums can be made of steel, dense paperboard (commonly called a **fibre drum**), or plastic, and are generally used for the transportation and storage of liquids and powders.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums are often stackable, and have dimensions designed for efficient warehouse and logistics use.
[src:tonne/drum-container] This type of packaging is frequently certified for transporting dangerous goods.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Proper shipment requires the drum to comply with all applicable regulations.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Steel drums are ubiquitous industrial shipping containers.
[src:tonne/drum-container] They are manufactured from sheets of cold rolled steel formed into a tube and welded along the side seam.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Stainless steel, nickel, and special alloys are occasionally used.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The bottom head is permanently attached by the manufacturer.
[src:tonne/drum-container] They were first utilized by the Axis powers (Germany and Italy), but were quickly adopted by Allies.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The drums helped win the Guadalcanal campaign in the first U.S. offensive in the South Pacific Theater.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Navy could not maintain command of the sea long enough to offload aviation gasoline for aircraft ashore, so the drums were often transported to the island on fast ships, such as destroyers, and shoved over the sides (or, time permitting, lowered in cargo nets).
[src:tonne/drum-container] Because gasoline's density is much less than that of water, the drums floated.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Navy Seabees in small craft corralled the drums.
[src:tonne/drum-container] A wide variety of constructions and sizes are available.
[src:tonne/drum-container] When the intended use is for shipment of dangerous goods (hazardous materials), strict regulatory requirements are applicable.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Coordinated by the UN, countries and regional authorities require drum construction and the demonstrated performance of severe testing.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The Industrial Steel Drum Institute has also provided guidance for conducting the tests.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums have embossed symbols to identify certification for shipment of certain types of products.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Many drums nominally measure just under 880 millimetres (35 in) tall with a diameter just under 610 millimetres (24 in), and have a common nominal volume of 208 litres (55 US gal) whereas the barrel volume of crude oil is 42 US gallons (159 L).
[src:tonne/drum-container] In the United States, 25-US-gallon (95-litre) drums are also in common use and have the same height.
[src:tonne/drum-container] This allows easy stacking of mixed pallets.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Barrels can be constructed of plastic, laminated paperboard or steel.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums have top and (usually) bottom *chimes* or rims: sometimes called *chines*.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Most steel drums have reinforcing *rolling hoops* or rings of thickened metal or plastic.
[src:tonne/drum-container] This sufficiently strengthens them so that they can readily be turned on their sides and rolled when filled with heavy materials, like liquids.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Over short to medium distances, drums can be tipped and rolled on the bottom rim while being held at an angle, balanced, and rotated with a two-handed top grip that also supplies the torque (rotational or rolling force).
[src:tonne/drum-container] The open-top sub-type is sealed by a mechanical ring clamp (concave inwards) that exerts sufficient pressure to hold many non-volatile liquids and make an airtight seal against a gasket, as it exerts force inward and downward when tightened by a normal three-quarter inch wrench or ratchet wrench.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Tops exist with bung holes as above, and these hybrid drums with lid can be used to ship many non-volatile liquids as well as industrial powders.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Many drums are used to ship and store powdered products as well as liquids, such as plastic beads for injection moulding, extrusion, and purified industrial grade powders like cleansers (e.g., fertilizers, and powdered aluminum).
[src:tonne/drum-container] If used to transport dangerous goods across international boundaries, they may need to have UN certification.
[src:tonne/drum-container] In general, drum usage is limited to wholesale distribution of bulk products, which are then further processed or sub-divided in a factory.
[src:tonne/drum-container] These metal drums have two openings with flanges, often 51 millimetres (2 in) NPS and 19 millimetres (0.75 in) NPS in diameter.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Once the drums are filled, the plugs (bungs) are screwed in the flanges using pneumatic or hand-operated bung tightener (plug wrench).
[src:tonne/drum-container] To secure the contents of the drums against theft and adulteration during shipment, cap-seals made of metal and other types like metal-plastic laminates are used.
[src:tonne/drum-container] These cap-seals sit on top of the flanges and are crimped, using a drum cap-seal crimping tool, also called a drum cap sealer.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Once cap-seals are crimped, the plugs can be unscrewed only by breaking these cap-seals.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Pneumatic and hand-operated cap-seal crimping tools are available.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Pneumatic ones are used in production lines for high production.
[src:tonne/drum-container] A 200-litre drum (known as a 55-gallon drum in the United States and a 44-gallon drum in the United Kingdom and the rest of the world) is a cylindrical container with a nominal capacity of 200 litres (55 US or 44 imp gal).
[src:tonne/drum-container] The exact capacity varies by manufacturer, purpose, or other factors.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Standard drums have inside dimensions of 572 millimetres (22.5 in) diameter and 851 millimetres (33.5 in) height.
[src:tonne/drum-container] These dimensions yield a volume of about 218.7 litres (57.8 US gal; 48.1 imp gal), but they are commonly filled to about 200 litres.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The outside dimensions of a 200-litre drum are typically 584 millimetres (23 in) diameter at the top or bottom rim, 597 millimetres (23.5 in) diameter at the chines (ridges around drum), and 876 millimetres (34.5 in) height.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Exact dimensions are specified in ANSI MH2.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The drums are typically made of steel with a ribbed outer wall to improve rigidity and for rolling.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The lids can be welded or secured with a head gasket and bolt ring.
[src:tonne/drum-container] They are commonly used for transporting oils, fuels, chemicals, and dry goods.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums are frequently transported on pallets for ease of handling by a fork truck and for shipping.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The drum's size, shape, and weight distribution lends itself to being moved about readily on the loading dock or factory floor with a two-wheeled hand truck.
[src:tonne/drum-container] They can also be moved by hand short distances on firm surfaces by tilting and then rolling along the base, or by using a drum handler, which is designed especially for that purpose.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Closed-head steel barrels and drums used for shipment of chemicals and petroleum products have a standardised bunghole arrangement, with one 51-millimetre (2 in) (DN50) NPT and one 19-millimetre (3⁄4 in) (DN20) NPT threaded bunghole on opposite sides of the top head.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums can also be made of durable plastic or paperboard and this arrangement is echoed in many plastic drums.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Various components can be mounted to the drum, such as drum pumps and bung mixers.
[src:tonne/drum-container] In the past, hazardous waste was often placed in drums of this size and stored in open fields or buried.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Over time, some drums would corrode and leak.
[src:tonne/drum-container] As a result, these drums have become iconic of pollution problems, even though they have numerous uses and are ubiquitous in commerce.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Tests have shown that a leaking 55-gallon drum can disperse its contents over a 1,200 square-foot area of level surface.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums are often cleaned or re-conditioned and then used for storing or shipping various liquids or materials.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Although crude oil is sometimes shipped in 55-US-gallon drums, the measurement standard of oil in barrels is based on the whiskey containers of the 1870s that measured 42 US gallons (35 imp gal; 159 L).
[src:tonne/drum-container] The measure of 42 US or wine gallons corresponds to a wine tierce (third-pipe).
[src:tonne/drum-container] Steel drums are commonly reconditioned for further use.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Life cycle studies of reconditioning and reuse have been quite favorable.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Clean drums go to a qualified reconditioner: hazardous residue can be a concern to regulators.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Reconditioning usually consists of inspection, removal of labels, cleaning (mechanical, heat, or caustic cleaner), straightening of dents and chimes, replacement of gaskets, painting, testing, marking and labeling.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Steel drums can often go through many use - reconditioning - reuse cycles before they are recycled or landfilled.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Fibre drums (occasionally: fiber drums) are shipping containers with paperboard : laminated paperboard; plastics, foils, and other protective layers.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The heads can be of fibreboard, metal, plywood, plastic or other suitable material.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Drums typically have a circular cross section but square drums are also available: these can be packed closer during shipment and storage.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Fibre drums are available in a variety of constructions and sizes.
[src:tonne/drum-container] They are used for shipping various granular materials, coiled wire and cable, long Fluorescent light bulbs, and (when certified) for dangerous goods.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Compatibility with the contents is important; drum liners are commonly used.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Steel, fibre, and plastic covers are available with steel lever lock ring closures.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Plastic drums are typically made of blow molded high density polyethylene.
[src:tonne/drum-container] They are available in a variety of sizes and constructions designed for specific purposes and markets.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Plastic drums are used for liquids, granular solids, and inner packages.
[src:tonne/drum-container] When designed, tested, and labeled, plastic drums can be used with dangerous goods or hazardous materials.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The plastic drum, inner coating, or drum liner should be compatible with the intended contents.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Foods and pharmaceuticals can be particularly sensitive.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Some liquid chemicals can permeate through plastics or can cause embrittlement.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The compression stability of plastic drums can be sensitive to heat.
[src:tonne/drum-container] The Plastic Drum Institute does not recommend stacking when temperatures are above about 32 °C (90 °F).
[src:tonne/drum-container] Some methods of reinforcing the sidewalls are available.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Plastic drums are used for more than shipping containers.
[src:tonne/drum-container] They can be used for water collection and storage.
[src:tonne/drum-container] Also, plastic drums are used along highways to mark construction zones.
[src:tonne/tonne] The **tonne** (/tʌn/ ⓘ or /tɒn/; symbol: **t**) is a unit of mass equal to 1,000 kilograms.
[src:tonne/tonne] It is also referred to as a ***metric ton*** in the United States to distinguish it from the non-metric units of the *short ton* and the *long ton*.
[src:tonne/tonne] One tonne is equivalent to approximately 2,204.6 pounds, 1.102 short tons, and 0.984 long tons.
[src:tonne/tonne] The exact corresponding SI unit is the **megagram** (symbol **Mg**), a less common way to express the same mass.
[src:tonne/tonne] The BIPM symbol for the tonne is t, adopted at the same time as the unit in 1879.
[src:tonne/tonne] Its use is also official for the metric ton in the United States, having been adopted by the United States National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST).
[src:tonne/tonne] It is a symbol, not an abbreviation, and should not be followed by a period.
[src:tonne/tonne] Use of lower case is significant, and use of other letter combinations can lead to ambiguity.
[src:tonne/tonne] For example, T, MT, mT, are the SI symbols for the tesla, megatesla, and millitesla, respectively, while Mt and mt are SI-compatible symbols for the megatonne (one teragram) and millitonne (one kilogram).
[src:tonne/tonne] If describing TNT equivalent units of energy, one megatonne of TNT is equivalent to approximately 4.184 petajoules.
[src:tonne/tonne] In English, *tonne* is an established spelling alternative to *metric ton*.
[src:tonne/tonne] In American English and British English, tonne is usually pronounced the same as ton (/tʌn/), but the final "e" can also be pronounced, i.e.
[src:tonne/tonne] In Australian English, the common and recommended pronunciation is /tɒn/.
[src:tonne/tonne] In the United States, *metric ton* is the name for this unit used and recommended by NIST; an unqualified mention of a *ton* typically refers to a short ton of 2000 lb (907.2 kg) and to a lesser extent to a long ton of 2240 lb (1016 kg), with the term *tonne* rarely used in speech or writing.
[src:tonne/tonne] Both terms are acceptable in Canadian English.
[src:tonne/tonne] The spelling *tonne* pre-dates the introduction of the SI in 1960; it has been used with this meaning in France since 1842, when there were no metric prefixes for multiples of 106 and above, and is now used as the standard spelling for the metric mass measurement in most English-speaking countries.
[src:tonne/tonne] In the United States, the unit was originally referred to using the French words *millier* or *tonneau*, but these terms are now obsolete.
[src:tonne/tonne] The British imperial and United States customary units are comparable to the *tonne* and the spelling of *ton* in English is the same, though they differ in mass.
[src:tonne/tonne] Prior to metrification the French tonne consisted of 2000 French pounds (livres).
[src:tonne/tonne] Therefore a French tonne of that era weighed 979 kg compared to an English ton of 1016 kg.
[src:tonne/tonne] Prior to the use of tonne for this weight tonneau (plural: tonneaux) was used.
[src:tonne/tonne] A tonne is the mass of one cubic metre of pure water at 4 °C (39 °F).
[src:tonne/tonne] As a non-SI unit, the use of SI metric prefixes with the tonne does not fall within the SI standard.
[src:tonne/tonne] For multiples of the tonne, it is more usual to speak of thousands or millions of tonnes.
[src:tonne/tonne] Kilotonne, megatonne, and gigatonne are more usually used for the energy of nuclear explosions and other events in equivalent mass of TNT, often loosely as approximate figures.
[src:tonne/tonne] When used in this context, there is little need to distinguish between metric and other tons, and the unit is spelled either as *ton* or *tonne* with the relevant prefix attached.
[src:tonne/tonne] Values in the equivalent short and long tons columns are rounded to five significant figures.
[src:tonne/tonne] Though non-standard, the symbol "kt" is also used (instead of the standard symbol "kn") for knot, a unit of speed for aircraft and watercraft.
[src:tonne/tonne] The standard meaning of the symbol kt is for kilotonne.
[src:tonne/tonne] A **metric ton unit** (mtu) can mean 10 kg (22 lb) within metal trading, particularly within the United States.
[src:tonne/tonne] It traditionally referred to a metric ton of ore containing 1% (i.e.
[src:tonne/tonne] — Walter L Pohl, *Economic Geology: Principles and Practices*, English edition, 2011, p.
[src:tonne/tonne] In the case of uranium, *MTU* is sometimes used in the sense of *metric ton of uranium* (1000 kg [2200 lb]).
[src:tonne/tonne] The *tonne of trinitrotoluene (TNT)* is used as a proxy for energy, usually of explosions (TNT is a common high explosive).
[src:tonne/tonne] Prefixes are used: kiloton(ne), megaton(ne), gigaton(ne), especially for expressing nuclear weapon yield, based on a specific combustion energy of TNT of about 4.2 MJ/kg (or one thermochemical calorie per milligram).
[src:tonne/tonne] One tonne of TNT is approximately equivalent to 4.2 gigajoules.
[src:tonne/tonne] In the petroleum industry, the tonne of oil equivalent (toe) is a unit of energy: the amount of energy released by burning one tonne of crude oil, approximately 42 GJ.
[src:tonne/tonne] There are several slightly different definitions.
[src:tonne/tonne] This is ten times as much as a tonne of TNT because atmospheric oxygen is used.
[src:tonne/tonne] Like the gram and the kilogram, the tonne gave rise to a (now obsolete) force unit of the same name, the tonne-force, equivalent to about 9.8 kilonewtons.
[src:tonne/tonne] The unit is also often called simply "tonne" or "metric ton" without identifying it as a unit of force.
